# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] The **2011 ACC Women's Twenty20 Championship** was an international women's cricket tournament held in Kuwait from 18 to 25 February 2011.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] It was organised by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] Ten teams participated in the tournament, down from twelve at the previous edition in 2009.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] Iran and Qatar were the teams that did not return.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] The ten teams were divided into groups of five, one of which was topped by China and the other by Nepal.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] China defeated Thailand in the first semi-final, but Nepal were defeated by Hong Kong in the other.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] Hong Kong went on to also defeat China in the final, winning their second consecutive title.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] The Afghanistan women's national cricket team was scheduled to make its debut at the tournament, but was forced to withdraw before travelling to Kuwait due to elements in Afghanistan opposing women's participation in sport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] The top five runscorers are included in this table, ranked by runs scored and then by batting average.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2011-acc-women-s-twenty20-championship] The top five wicket-takers are listed in this table, ranked by wickets taken and then by bowling average.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Taliban insurgent group and allied militants conducted a military offensive in 2021 that led to the fall of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and the end of the nearly 20-year war in Afghanistan that had begun following the United States invasion of the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Taliban victory had widespread domestic and international ramifications regarding human rights and proliferation of terrorism.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The offensive included a continuation of the bottom-up succession of negotiated or paid surrenders to the Taliban from the village level upwards that started following the February 2020 US–Taliban deal.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The offensive began on 1 May 2021, coinciding with the withdrawal of the United States's 2,500 troops in Afghanistan, and those belonging to other international allies.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Large numbers of armed civilians, including women, volunteered with the Afghan Army in defense, while some former warlords, notably Ismail Khan, were also recruited.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Despite this, the Taliban managed to make significant territorial gains in the countryside, increasing the number of districts it controlled from 73 to 223 in the first three months of the offensive.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 6 August, the Taliban launched an assault on the provincial capitals, with most of the towns surrendering without a fight, culminating with victories in weeks-long battles of major cities Herat, Kandahar and Lashkargah on 13 August.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The speed of the Taliban's takeover came as a surprise to many, including the governments of the United States and their allies, Russia and the Taliban themselves.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Factors in the ANSF loss to the Taliban included the February 2020 and April 2021 drops in US support, in which technical, proprietary software and logistics support, in particular aerial support, that the ANSF had been trained to depend on, were suddenly removed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Cronyism in ANSF military appointments and president Ashraf Ghani's inability to create an effective national consensus and convince local warlords were also seen as key processes of the ANSF's defeat.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Afghans are also more loyal towards their traditional ethnic, tribal and even familial ties than they are to a central government in Kabul, which the provincial Taliban commanders exploited to negotiate surrender of many troops.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In the long-term, the American invasion of Iraq and its shifting in focus to that region has also been cited as a reason for the Taliban's resurgence in the mid to late 2000s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In September 2020, over 5,000 Taliban prisoners, including 400 accused or convicted of major crimes such as murder, were released by the Afghan government as part of the United States–Taliban deal between the United States and the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] According to Afghanistan's National Security Council, many of the released prisoners who were "experts" returned to the battlefield and strengthened the Taliban's hand.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Also by the time of Taliban's final offensive, most of the Afghan provincial governors had cut deals with the militants to switch sides and join the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] A senior Afghan Interior Ministry official, quoted by the Washington Post, said that Taliban have recruitment teams that reach out to Afghan officials and push them to join the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] He says that Afghan government suspects that a long list of governors might have Taliban ties.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Taliban also enjoyed substantial support by various other armed militant groups, especially al-Qaeda and its associates like Jamaat Ansarullah.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Militants of al-Qaeda in the Indian Subcontinent (AQIS) reportedly fought alongside the Taliban in the 2021 offensive.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In the south and east, various Pakistani militant groups supported the Taliban offensive including Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan (which had about 5,000 fighters in Afghanistan), Harkat-ul-Mujahideen, Lashkar-e-Taiba, and Jaish-e-Mohammed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In May, the Taliban captured 15 districts from the Afghan government, including Nirkh and Jalrez Districts in Maidan Wardak Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Among the locations captured was the Dahla Dam in Kandahar Province, Afghanistan's second largest dam.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] During the month, 405 Afghan National Security Force (ANSF) troops and 260 civilians were killed in clashes, while the Afghan Ministry of Defense claimed to have killed 2,146 Taliban fighters including a Taliban divisional commander, Qari Jabar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] By the end of May, Portugal, Slovenia, Spain, and Sweden had completely withdrawn their forces from Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In June, the Taliban captured 69 districts from the Afghan government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] They entered the cities of Kunduz and Puli Khumri and besieged Mazar-i-Sharif.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Among the locations they captured was Afghanistan's main border crossing with Tajikistan and the Saydabad District in Maidan Wardak Province, which is called the gateway to Afghanistan's capital city, Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] They captured 700 trucks and Humvees from the Afghan security forces, and dozens of armored vehicles, Boeing Insitu ScanEagle drones and artillery systems.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] An Afghan Air Force Mil Mi-17 was shot down by the Taliban, killing three pilots, while a UH-60 Black Hawk was damaged on the ground after an outpost belonging to the Afghan Armed Forces was shelled by the Taliban in the same month.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 16 June, Taliban fighters executed 22 surrendering Afghan Army commandoes in the town of Dawlat Abad.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Among the dead was Major Sohrab Azimi, son of retired General Zahir Azimi.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] He was posthumously promoted to brigadier general.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Eyewitnesses said that the language the Taliban fighters spoke among themselves was foreign, indicating that the fighters were not from the area.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] During the month, 703 Afghan National Security Forces and 208 civilians were killed in clashes, while the Ministry of Defense claimed to have killed 1,535 Taliban fighters.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 19 June, President Ashraf Ghani replaced the Afghan National Army chief of staff, and the defense and interior ministers.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] By the end of June, all Resolute Support Mission's member countries had withdrawn their troops, except for the UK, Turkey, and the US.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 22 June, the Taliban captured Sher Khan Bandar, Afghanistan's main Tajikistan border crossing, and 13 districts fell to them within 24 hours.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, there was heavy fighting in Baghlan Province when Afghan forces launched an operation on the outskirts of Pul-e-Khumri, the provincial capital, killing 17 Taliban fighters, including Qari Khalid, a Taliban divisional commander.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Simultaneously, Taliban forces took control of Balkh and encircled Mazar-i-Sharif, the capital of Balkh Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 23 June, Taliban and Afghan forces clashed inside Pul-e Khumri.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 25 June, the Taliban took control of the Shinwari District and the Ghorband District in Parwan Province, north of Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] That same day NBC News reported that the Taliban "were surprised at the speed of their advance and had avoided capturing some targets so as not to run afoul of the US", and the Afghan government launched a program called National Mobilization that aimed to arm militia groups to fight the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Meanwhile, Taliban deputy emir Sirajuddin Haqqani issued a series of instructions on *Voice of Jihad* for the governance of territories seized in the offensive.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] *FDD's Long War Journal* researcher Thomas Joscelyn argued that Haqqani's statements "read like those that would be issued by the head of a nation".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 27 June, Chaki Wardak District and Saydabad District fell to the Taliban after at least 50 Afghan troops surrendered and were captured by the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day Rustaq District, Shortepa District and the Arghistan District fell to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] ToloNews reported that 108 districts fell to the Taliban in the last two months and the Afghan army had retaken only 10.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 29 June, the Taliban launched an offensive on Ghazni, causing violent clashes within the city.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In July, the Taliban captured 64 districts from the Afghan government and entered the second and third largest cities of Afghanistan, Kandahar and Herat respectively.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] During the month, 335 Afghan National Security Forces and 189 civilians were killed during the clashes with the Taliban, while the Ministry of Defense claimed to have killed 3,159 Taliban fighters.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Around 1,500 Afghan soldiers deserted into Tajikistan, according to its Collective Security Treaty Organization (CSTO) envoy.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Iranian media reported that around 300 Afghan soldiers and civilians had crossed the border and entered Iran to escape the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 2 July, Germany and Italy withdrew their troops from Afghanistan, and US troops left Bagram Airfield, handing it to the Afghan Armed Forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Subsequent US airstrikes against the Taliban were led from the Al Udeid Air Base in Qatar and the US Navy carrier strike group in the Persian Gulf, requiring the warplanes to travel several hours to reach their targets.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] According to a US defence official, these airstrikes amounted to only "a handful" each day.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the first weekend of July, hundreds of armed women took to the streets of northern and central Afghanistan in demonstrations against the Taliban offensive, the largest one taking place in Chaghcharan, the capital of Ghor Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The provincial governor Abdulzahir Faizzada reported in an interview with *The Guardian* that many Afghan women, some of whom recently escaped the Taliban, have been learning to use firearms in order to defend themselves, with some having already battled the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Taliban spokesperson Zabiullah Mujahid denounced the reports as "propaganda" and declared that "women will never pick up guns against us".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] During the weekend, the Taliban captured nine border posts belonging to the Afghan Army in Kunar Province near the border with Pakistan, during which 39 personnel of the Afghan Army surrendered to the Taliban while another 31 fled to Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 5 July, Tajik President Emomali Rahmon announced the deployment of 20,000 troops on the Afghanistan–Tajikistan border, to prevent a spillover of the war into Tajikistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 9 July, the Collective Security Treaty Organization announced that the Russian Federation would deploy 7,000 troops on the border as well, to aid Tajikistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 7 July, pro-government forces defeated a Taliban attempt to capture the city of Qala e Naw.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 8 July, the Taliban captured the strategically important Karukh District in Herat Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 8 July, Abubaker Muradi, deputy head of National Directorate of Security (NDS), and Khir Mohammad Arefi, a commander of a territorial army, along with dozens of other security personnel surrendered to the Taliban without a fight.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Khan Jan Zafar and Mohammad Farid Akhizai, two members of the provincial council, also surrendered to the Taliban on the same day.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 10 July, the Taliban captured Panjwayi District in Kandahar Province and surrounded the city of Ghazni in central Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The border crossings of Torghundi with Turkmenistan and Islam Qala with Iran were captured by the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] During the capture of the Islam Qala border crossing, some Afghan security and customs officials fled across the border with Iran to escape the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 11 July, Australian Defence Minister Peter Dutton announced the end of its military presence in Afghanistan, with the last 80 personnel having left the country in recent weeks.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 12 July, the commander of US and NATO forces in Afghanistan Austin S.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The same day Afghanistan's foreign ministry announced that they have killed Taliban's intelligence chief, Kari Shagasi, and arrested two of his followers in Logar province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] As of 12 July, the Taliban had seized 148 districts from the Afghan government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 14 July, the Afghan border post at Spin Boldak was captured by the Taliban force; Reuters Indian journalist Danish Siddiqui was killed there while covering the fighting two days later.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 12 July, Turkmen President Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow ordered the deployment of troops, heavy weapons, and armour on the Afghanistan–Turkmenistan border, to prevent a spillover of the conflict into Turkmenistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 16 July, Uzbekistan hosted a conference between a number of the region's leaders and foreign diplomats, including Afghan President Ghani, to promote peace and prevent a civil war.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Later that month, the Taliban captured Wakhan District and so was also in control of the Afghanistan-China border.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 21 July, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Mark Milley reported that half of all Afghan districts were under Taliban control and that momentum was "sort of" on the side with the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 22 July, the Pentagon confirmed that the United States Air Force had carried out four airstrikes in Afghanistan at the request of Afghan officials.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Two airstrikes were aimed at destroying military equipment captured by the Taliban from Afghan security forces; one artillery gun and one military vehicle were destroyed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Meanwhile, the battle for Kandahar city continued, with the settlement being essentially besieged by the rebels.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] All surrounding districts save for Daman District had fallen under Taliban control, and only Kandahar's air field (crucial for supplying the local security forces) remained under full government control.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] According to the *FDD's Long War Journal*, the fall of Daman District to the insurgents would make it extremely difficult for the government forces to hold Kandahar city.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 22 July 100 people were killed in a mass shooting in Spin Boldak, Kandahar Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Pro-government forces gained victories in Bamyan Province, as local militias and the police retook the districts of Sayghan and Kahmard from the Taliban, and in Herat Province, where the government recaptured Karakh District.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 24 July, the government imposed a curfew between 10 p.m. and 4 a.m. in all but three provinces of the country, to "curb violence and reduce the movements and advances of the Taliban".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 25 July, a key Taliban commander, Mufti Ismael, was injured and five of his guards were killed in a mine blast targeting their convoy in Faryab province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 26 July, a report by representative of the United Nations Deborah Lyons showed a sharp increase in civilian deaths as a consequence of the fighting between the government and the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Lyons implored both sides to protect civilians as she says that women and children are being killed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The same day around 46 Afghan troops, including 5 officers, sought refuge in Pakistan after they were unable to defend their military post.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] By 31 July, the Taliban had entered the provincial capitals of both Helmand and Herat provinces, capturing scores of districts in the provinces and also capturing border crossings with Iran and Turkmenistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Among others, Herat's important Karakh District was again overrun by the rebels.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The insurgents also cut the road between Herat International Airport and Herat city, although the airport remained under government control.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The *Long War Journal* argued that the government's ability to keep control of Herat city without the airport supplying the defenders was questionable.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Meanwhile, Kandahar city remained contested.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] From 1 to 2 August, the Safian, Qala-e-Kohneh and Kariz areas on the outskirts of Lashkar Gah fell to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Clashes between Taliban and the government also took place in the suburbs of the city, with the Afghan Air Force and United States Air Force attacking Taliban positions.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 2 August 40 civilians were killed and more than 100 wounded in the fighting.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] After capturing Lashkar Gah's radio station, the Taliban began broadcasting their *Voice of Sharia* programming.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The rebels also began to attack the city's airport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Meanwhile, the government dispatched reinforcements to prevent the city from falling to the insurgents.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 3 August 13 people—including five attackers—were killed in a Taliban bombing and shootout in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The inghimasi-style operation, carried out by the Taliban's "Martyrdom Battalion", aimed at killing Defence Minister Bismillah Khan Mohammadi; he survived the attack.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Mohammadi was described by the *Long War Journal* as one of the key government figures responsible for countering the Taliban offensive.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] As of 5 August 115 Afghan National Security Forces personnel and 58 civilians were killed during the clashes with the Taliban, while the Ministry of Defense claimed to have killed 3,197 Taliban fighters since the start of the month.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 6 August, the Taliban assassinated Dawa Khan Minapal, head of the Government Media and Information Centre, in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, heavy fighting was reported in Jowzjan Province as the Taliban entered the provincial capital, Sheberghan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Taliban confirmed responsibility for the killing of Minapal and warned that it would target senior administration officials in retaliation for increasing airstrikes.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, the Taliban captured the provincial capital of Nimroz Province, Zaranj, making it the first capture by the Taliban of a provincial capital since the 2001 American invasion.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Taliban executed dozens of captured soldiers in the province, and gouged out eyes of some.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The rebels proceeded to open the local prisons, allowing many inmates to escape.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] As Zaranj had reportedly been captured with almost no resistance, Afghan journalist Bilal Sarwary voiced suspicions that someone had "sold" the city to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Social media posts suggested that the Taliban were welcomed by some residents of the city which has a long history of lawlessness.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Images appearing on social media showed Taliban fighters driving captured military Humvees, luxury SUVs and pickups through the streets while flying Taliban flags as local residents—mostly youths and young men—cheered them on.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] A UN envoy also warned the country was entering a 'deadlier phase' of the war.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The governments of Britain and United States warned its citizens to leave Afghanistan "immediately" amid the Taliban advance and the worsening security situation.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 7 August, the Taliban had captured Sheberghan, making it the second capture of a provincial capital.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Abdul Rashid Dostum, the ex-warlord and the strongman who had traditionally dominated the city, took his followers and fled to Khwaja Du Koh District, the only area in Jowzjan Province which was still government-held.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Meanwhile, pro-government forces had been reduced to a pocket of resistance in Lashkar Gah, while Kandahar and Herat remained fiercely contested.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Insurgents also launched repeated raids on the other provincial capitals.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, US B-52 bombers carried out airstrikes against Taliban in Afghanistan, operating from Al Udeid Air Base in Qatar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The United States was also using armed Reaper drones and AC-130 Spectre gunships which reportedly began daily attacks against targets around Kandahar, Herat, and Lashkar Gah.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] USS *Ronald Reagan* was launching fast jets to provide support to the missions.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The American Embassy in Kabul urged all Americans to leave the country immediately due to increased security concerns, and the inability of the embassy to guarantee the safety of American citizens due to the reduction of staff at the embassy.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The following day, the Taliban captured the cities of Kunduz and Sar-e Pol after heavy clashes with the Afghan National Security Forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In the battles for the two cities, mass desertions were reported, as many Afghan National Army soldiers had been demotivated by the rapid rebel advance as well as Taliban propaganda.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Pro-government forces were only able to hold onto Kunduz's military base and airport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The battle for Kunduz involved the Red Unit, the Taliban elite shock troops, and resulted in the release of hundreds of prisoners including Taliban commanders.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The city of Taloqan was also taken by the Taliban late 8 August, making it the fifth provincial capital to fall.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Government forces retreated from the city after noon, retaking Warsaj District and Farkhar District.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 9 August, the Taliban captured Aybak, the capital of Samangan Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Deputy governor Sefatullah Samangani told the AFP news agency that government forces had withdrawn from the city without a fight after community representatives had requested that it be spared more violence.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, Asif Azimi, a former senator from Samangan and a prominent warlord from the Jamiat-e Islami party, defected to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Azimi said hundreds of men under his command had also defected to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] President Ashraf Ghani and other political leaders also agreed to form a joint command center to coordinate and assist with public uprising forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Fighting intensified around Mazar-i-Sharif on 10 August.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In Farah, capital of Farah Province, the Taliban had taken control of the governor's compound after heavy fighting between the Taliban and government forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] They had also taken control of the police headquarters and prison.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Although heavy fighting continued, Farah became the seventh provincial capital to fall.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] An eighth provincial capital, Puli Khumri of Baghlan Province, was also captured on 10 August.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 11 August, Fayzabad of Badakhshan Province became the ninth provincial capital to be captured by the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] After the Taliban reached the city gates, government forces decided to retreat to Farkhar District and join with security forces there from Taloqan's fall.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Prior to the US invasion, Fayzabad had been the headquarters of the Northern Alliance.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, the Taliban captured Kunduz Airport and a major military base belonging to 217 Pamir Corps after hundreds of Afghan troops surrendered, securing Taliban control over their military equipment in Kunduz.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Deutsche Presse-Agentur (dpa) quoted two local councillors who said that the entire 217th Pamir Corps surrendered to Taliban forces in Kunduz.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] A Taliban spokesman also posted a video on Twitter which purportedly showed government soldiers joining the militants' ranks.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The besieged troops of the 217 Pamir Corps had held out for three days before surrendering; much military equipment was captured by the rebels at the base and airport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Additionally, the day saw General Wali Mohammad Ahmadzai's replacement by General Haibatullah Alizai as the new Afghan Army chief of staff.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The outgoing General Ahmadzai served as an Afghan army chief of staff since he assumed the post in June 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 12 August, the Taliban captured the city of Ghazni, making it the tenth provincial capital to fall within a week.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The city lies along the Kabul–Kandahar Highway, serving as a gateway between Kabul and the strongholds in the south.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Governor of Ghazni Province was soon arrested in Wardak for "surrendering without a fight" in exchange for safe passage.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, the central government offered a proposal of "power-sharing" in lieu of ceasefire; the Taliban rejected this offer stating that it wanted to establish a new Islamic emirate.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The same day also saw the fall of strategic Shindand Air Base in Herat and capture of two UH-60 Black Hawk helicopters stationed in the Air Base.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Late that night, Herat, Afghanistan's third-largest city and the capital of the eponymous province, fell to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The fall of Herat, after two weeks of siege, forced Ismail Khan and other top government officials and forces to seek refuge at a provincial airport and the army corps outside the city.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In the morning, Khan along with Abdul Rahman Rahman, deputy interior minister, and Hasib Sediqi, Chief of National Directorate of Security in Herat, surrendered to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The commander of 207 Zafar Corps, Khyal Nabi Ahmadzai, and thousands of government forces also surrendered to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] According to the local officials, an entire Afghan army Corps in the city of Herat crumbled.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] By this point, they controlled 11 of Afghanistan's 34 provincial capitals.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Taliban had also launched an assault on Qala e Naw, capturing the city after failing to do so in July.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Overnight, Kandahar was captured by the Taliban: heavy clashing around the city led to the withdrawal of the ANA, thus increasing the number of provincial capitals controlled by the Taliban to thirteen.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] After several weeks of fighting in the Battle of Lashkargah, the city of Lashkargah, capital of Helmand Province, was captured by the Taliban on 13 August.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, the Taliban took control of Chaghcharan (also called Firozkoh), the capital city of Ghor Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Officials said the city fell without any fighting, becoming the fifteenth provincial capital to fall to the Taliban within a week.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Firozkoh had a population of nearly 132,000 people.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Later on 13 August, the Taliban captured Puli Alam, Qalat and Tarinkot, the capitals of Logar, Zabul and Uruzgan Provinces respectively.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Government loyalists put up a determined defense in Logar before being overrun, while Zabul and Uruzgan were only surrendered to the rebels after the local defenders judged their situation to be untenable and opted to retreat.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In contrast, Qalat and Fayroz Koh fell without any fighting.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Qalat had been deprived of defenders who had been sent to Kandahar, and Fayroz Koh officials preferred to negiotiate a takeover instead of being "steamrolled by the Taliban offensive".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The *Long War Journal* argued that the fall of these provincial capitals allowed the Taliban to besiege Kabul, and described the Afghan government as being on the "verge of collapse".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 14 August 2021, the Taliban captured seven provincial capital cities; Gardez, Sharana, Asadabad, Maymana, Mihtarlam, Nili, and Mazar-i-Sharif, the fourth-largest city in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Two long-time anti-Taliban warlords, namely Dostum and Atta Muhammad Nur, fled to Uzbekistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Abas Ebrahimzada, a lawmaker from the Balkh province, said that in Mazar-i-Sharif, the national army surrendered first which caused the pro-government militia and other forces to lose morale and surrender in the face of Taliban assault on the city.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Zabihullah Mohmand, the corps commander of Mazar-i-Sharif, also surrendered to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Following the loss of the city, Atta Muhammad Nur stated in a Facebook post that his defeat in Mazar-i-Sharif was planned and held the government forces responsible for the defeat.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] He did not specify who was behind the conspiracy, nor provide any detail other than saying that he and Dostum are in a safe place.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Later, Taliban forces also entered Maidan Shar, center of Maidan Wardak Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] At this point, the rebels had encircled Kabul, while the Afghan National Army had descended into chaos following its rapid defeat across the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Only the 201st Corps and 111th Division, both based at the Afghan capital, were left operational.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Early on 15 August 2021, the Taliban entered Jalalabad, the capital of Nangarhar Province, unopposed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] It was the twenty-sixth provincial capital to fall, and its capture left Kabul as the last major city under Afghan government control.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Soon afterward, Maidan Shar, Khost, Bamyan, Mahmud-i-Raqi, Charikar and Parun also fell.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Afghan commandos managed to successfully evacuate Kandahar Airport on the same day; the airport had still been held by government loyalists up to this point.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Security forces surrendered Bagram Airfield to the Taliban; the airbase housed around 5,000 Taliban and Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant prisoners.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Also on 15 August, authorities in Uzbekistan detained 84 Afghan soldiers who had crossed the border, and provided medical aid to both the detained soldiers and a group of soldiers which had gathered on the Afghan side of the Termez-Khairaton bridge.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 16 August, the Khost Protection Force (KPF), a militia unit created by the CIA in the early years of the US invasion, surrendered to Taliban forces in eastern Afghanistan after attempting to flee to Paktia Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] According to local journalists cited by Interfax, about 6,000 KPF in 1,200 vehicles surrendered to the Taliban, with a video of the surrender being posted to social media.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Officials said that the first deployment would occur in the next 24 to 48 hours, and that it would be completed by the end of the month.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] According to those sources, charter aircraft were to be used for the evacuation, as the Kabul airport still allowed commercial airliners to fly at the time; military aircraft were to be used if that became impossible.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] According to the British government, the evacuation and its timing had long been planned, but an Afghan official said that the timing was brought forward as the security situation rapidly deteriorated.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] In addition to the 3,000 US troops, an additional 3,500 were placed on standby in Kuwait in case the situation escalated to a renewed armed conflict with the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Canada announced that Canadian special forces units will be deployed to evacuate embassy personnel in Kabul, which houses Afghan families who have worked with Canadian staff in the past.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Danish and Norwegian governments announced that their embassies in Kabul would close for security reasons, and proceeded to evacuate their diplomatic staff and Afghans who worked alongside them.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 15 August, despite issuing a statement saying it had no plans to take the Afghan capital "by force", the Taliban entered the outskirts of Kabul from multiple directions, including Kalakan District, Qarabagh District, and Paghman District.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] A citywide blackout and possible assault and inmate uprising at Pul-e-Charkhi prison was reported.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Boeing CH-47 Chinook and Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk helicopters began landing at the American embassy in Kabul to carry out evacuations and diplomats were rapidly shredding classified documents.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Afghan interior ministry announced that President Ghani had decided to relinquish power and an interim government led by the Taliban would be formed; former president Hamid Karzai was to be part of the negotiation team.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Taliban ordered its fighters to wait for a peaceful transfer of power and to not enter Kabul by force.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 15 August it was reported that President Ghani had left the country for Tajikistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Ghani's departure from Afghanistan was criticised by many Afghans and outside observers.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Nikita Ishchenko, a spokesperson for Russia's embassy in Kabul, claimed that Ghani fled Afghanistan with four cars and helicopters full of money.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Speaking later from the United Arab Emirates, Ghani said he left on the advice of government aides to avoid being lynched (Afghan President Mohammad Najibullah had been publicly hanged upon the previous Taliban takeover in 1996).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] He denied reports that he had taken large sums of money with him, noting that he had passed through customs on his arrival in the UAE.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] It was also considered "unlikely" by the Special Inspector General for Afghanistan Reconstruction (SIGAR), who nonetheless argues that Ghani took 500.000 US dollars with him while escaping.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Late on 15 August, an Afghan Air Force Embraer 314 and Uzbekistan Air Force MiG-29 collided mid-air, with both aircraft crashing in Uzbekistan's Surxondaryo Region.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The pilots of both aircraft ejected and landed with parachutes.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Earlier in the day, Uzbekistan said it had detained 84 Afghan soldiers who had crossed the border seeking medical assistance while fleeing the Taliban's offensives.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 16 August, Taliban spokesman Mohammad Naeem said in an interview with Al Jazeera that war was over in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] He said that the Taliban have achieved what they wanted, they will not allow Afghanistan's territory to be used against anyone, nor do they want to harm anyone.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, Uzbekistan's prosecutor general office said that 22 military planes and 24 helicopters carrying around 585 Afghan soldiers had arrived in Uzbekistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Around 158 Afghan soldiers crossed the Uzbekistan's border on foot.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Pentagon confirmed the head of US Central Command in Qatar, General Kenneth F.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] McKenzie Jr., met Taliban leaders based in Qatar's capital Doha.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Taliban officials agreed to terms set by McKenzie for refugees to flee using Kabul Airport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 23 August, Taliban spokesperson Suhail Shaheen indicated that they would be unwilling to extend the 31 August deadline for withdrawal of US forces from Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The same day, the director of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), William J.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Burns, held a secret meeting in Kabul with Taliban leader Abdul Ghani Baradar, who returned to Afghanistan from exile in Qatar, to discuss the 31 August deadline.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Taliban committed a number of war crimes during their 2021 offensive.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 16 June, in Dawlat Abad, 22 unarmed Afghan special forces commandos were executed while attempting to surrender.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] A video of the event circulated widely and was broadcast by CNN.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Samira Hamidi of Amnesty International described the event as "the cold-blooded murder of surrendering soldiers – a war crime".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] She called for the event to be investigated as part of the International Criminal Court investigation in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 8 July, Afghan soldiers executed an Afghan villager by making him sit on an improvised explosive device (IED) before it exploded.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The victim, named Barakatullah, was accused of aiding the Taliban by Afghan police and anti-Taliban militia.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The father of Barakatullah denied that his son was working with the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The incident took place south of the city of Sharana, the capital of Paktika province, and the video of the incident was uploaded on TikTok.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] France 24 Observers team was able to verify and geolocate the video.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Fawad Aman, a spokesperson for the Afghan ministry of defence, denied that any such incident took place.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] An Afghan journalist, Naseeb Zadran, said that this not an isolated incident and reflects the impunity enjoyed by Afghan army.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 16 July, the Taliban killed Danish Siddiqui, a Pulitzer-winning journalist working for Reuters, in Kandahar province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] His body was later handed over to the Red Cross; health officials from India and Afghanistan claimed it had been badly mutilated by Taliban fighters.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 22 July, it was reported that gunmen killed at least 100 people in Spin Boldak District in Kandahar following the Taliban takeover of the district.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Afghan government blamed the Taliban for the killings.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Human rights groups blamed the Taliban for a series of revenge killings targeting people close to general Abdul Raziq Achakzai in Kandahar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 1 August, the Afghan Air Force bombed a small private hospital in Lashkargah city, killing one and injuring three others.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] Its owner claimed his hospital had been targeted because the air force erroneously believed Taliban fighters were receiving treatment there.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 6 August, Taliban forces claimed responsibility for the 5 August assassination of Dawa Khan Menapal, head of the governmental media and information centre, in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On the same day, during which the Taliban took control of Zaranj, human rights activist Laal Gul Laal stated that the execution of 30 soldiers by the Taliban was a war crime.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] According to TOLOnews, some of the soldiers were tortured and had their eyes removed by the Taliban before they were killed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] On 20 August, Amnesty International called a massacre of Hazaras by the Taliban a "horrifying indicator" for the future.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p01] The Hazara men were variously shot and tortured to death, with one strangled by his own scarf and with his arm muscles sliced off, and another with his body shot to pieces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Errors in the US coalition training of the ANSF were also blamed, along with Afghan police extorting locals and funding themselves by inventing ghost soldiers.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The sudden switch ANSF salary management in April 2021 to Afghan military administration led to months of unpaid ANSF salaries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Cronyism in ANSF military appointments and president Ashraf Ghani's inability to create an effective national consensus were also seen as key processes leading to the ANSF's defeat.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Local warlords' lack of confidence in national level political leadership contributed to their willingness to negotiate with or surrender to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Starting in early 2020, the Taliban started a bottom-up campaign of negotiations in rural villages with the lowest-ranked government officials.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Officials named the resulting deals "ceasefires".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to Afghan and US officials interviewed by Susannah George of *The Washington Post*, the word "ceasefire" was misleading, since the officials were paid by the Taliban to transfer ANSF weapons to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Continuing through to mid 2021, each successive surrender was used to help convince other governmental and village leaders and scale up in size to district level, to allow the Taliban forces to take control of much of Afghanistan without military fights.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] After US president Biden's April 2021 announcement confirming a full unconditional US withdrawal, the chain of surrenders accelerated, scaling up to province-level surrenders.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The chain of surrenders provided increased resources in terms of government vehicles for transporting Taliban forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to Afghan special forces officers interviewed by Susannah George, some of the surrenders were motivated by the payments, while others were due to opportunism – the desire to be on the winning side that became credible following the February 2020 US–Taliban deal.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Elizabeth Threlkeld, a former US state department official, said that the Taliban's rapid advance and peaceful surrender of some Afghan army units had encouraged many others to follow suit.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Taliban used online social media to convince Afghans that "the government was illegitimate" and that the Taliban would be successful in taking control of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Saad Mohseni, head of TOLOnews, stated that the Taliban's "outreach was fantastic" and that they "capitalised on intratribal, ethnic, religious and ideological differences to win over people" and exploited popular complaints against the government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] During the Afghan Civil War (1996–2001), resistance to the Taliban was strongest in northern Afghanistan, the base of the Northern Alliance.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to the Afghanistan Analysts Network, the Taliban's concentration of its forces in the north may have been an attempt to forestall the creation of a second Northern Alliance after the withdrawal of US forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Afghan government had not expected the Taliban to mount serious attacks in the north.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Andrew Watkins, senior analyst for Afghanistan at the International Crisis Group, said there was no evidence that the Taliban had increased their manpower to conduct this offensive, aside from utilising some of the 5,000 insurgents who had been released earlier.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Watkins believes that the end of US airstrikes changed the scenario.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] He says that the end of US airstrikes granted the insurgents freedom of movement and they were able to regroup, plan and strengthen their supply lines without fear of US airstrikes.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] An international official interviewed by Voice of America stated that the Taliban had been able to move their forces freely throughout Afghanistan after the US–Taliban deal with almost no intervention from the Afghan government forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to David Zucchino, writing in *The New York Times*, the ANSF followed US military advice to concentrate their forces on urban centres, allowing rural areas to be sacrificed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The result was that the Taliban took control of most of Afghanistan's main highways in the northern winter of 2020/2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Zucchino saw this as a key element of the ANSF losing the war against the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Taliban control of the highways blocked ANSF supply and reinforcement lines and yielded revenue to the Taliban who taxed truck drivers.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to Sami Sadat, a three-star general of the ANSF, the February 2020 US–Taliban deal resulted to an "effectively ... overnight" change in the rules for US air support for the Afghan armed forces, leading to a sudden increase in battle effectiveness by the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The April 2021 confirmation by US president Biden of the US pullout resulted in the loss of contractors, proprietary software and weapons systems including the Afghan army's helicopter missile-defence system.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Afghan army had been trained on a high-tech military model using helicopters, airstrikes and technically specialised reconnaissance units.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to Sadat, the loss of technical support made the US high-tech army model ineffective, losing helicopter support for resupplying military bases, and aerial and laser-guided weapons.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Ali Yawar Adili, country director of the Afghanistan Analysts Network, said that Afghan officials—including Ghani—never expected that the US would be halting logistical and air support to the Afghan forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Afghan troops were heavily dependent on logistical and air support provided by the US and they were deeply shocked when US support was withdrawn.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Military historian Frederick Kagan agreed that Biden's way of making, timing and announcing his April 2021 withdrawal decision was a key factor in the defeat of the ANSF.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] He argued that very few US allies, including NATO members, "have the capacity to provide their own advanced air power, air cover, intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance assets".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to official US "lessons learned" reports, the US coalition delayed its initial funding of the ANSF when the Taliban were weak after the 2001 US invasion, and when the Taliban were stronger, "[cut] corners on training and funding".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The errors in training led to provincial police extorting money from local residents and getting paid for ghost soldiers.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Corrupt Afghan army officers leading ghost battalions, who pocket the salaries of absent soldiers, were a known issue in the Afghan military.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In early 2019, at least 42,000 ghost soldiers were removed from the army's payroll.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] However, the same year Afghanistan's Ministry of Defense denied the existence of ghost soldiers in the Afghan military.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The ministry's spokesman, Rohullah Ahmadzai, said that all personnel of Afghan military have physical presence on their duties and those who were involved in corruption are under investigation by the ministry.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Many Afghans are more loyal towards their traditional ethnic, tribal and even familial ties than they are to the Afghan army, which the provincial Taliban commanders exploited to negotiate surrender of many troops.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Any sense of loyalty towards central government in Kabul is overshadowed by strong loyalty towards tribes and region.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Mike Martin, a former British army officer, said that Ghani lacked the political skills to keep Afghanistan's many different ethnic groups loyal to the idea of a national cause.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Veteran Italian general and a former Chief of Staff of International Security Assistance Force (ISAF), Giorgio Battisti, said the division of Afghanistan along the tribal lines and loyalties is "stronger than loyalty to any institution".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] He said that an ethnic Tajik Afghan sent to Helmand province does not understand why he has to defend ethnic Pashtun Afghans there.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Anatol Lieven, a British scholar-journalist, writes that Afghanistan "is divided along many lines, which often crisscross one another in highly confusing ways".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] There is tension and mistrust between different Afghan ethnic groups like Pashtuns, Tajiks, Uzbeks and Hazaras, and a deep divide between the liberal world of educated Afghans in Kabul and the people who live in the deeply conservative countryside.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Lieven says that while Afghanistan has a central government and an army, in practice the central government is incapable of extending its administration to most of its own territory, or of keeping its own followers loyal to the state rather than other centers of power.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On the other hand, the Taliban were united by a militant Islamist ideology.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] For years the Pentagon was responsible for paying salary directly to the Afghan soldiers.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The responsibility for those payment was transferred to the Kabul government since the announcement of planned withdrawal in April.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Since then numerous Afghan soldiers have complained that they have not been paid in months and in many cases their units were no longer receiving food, supplies or ammunition.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Wesley Clark, a former NATO supreme allied commander, told CNN that many Afghan soldiers saw the job in military as paycheck, and not a cause.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] He said that Afghan military is composed of various tribes and factions that were historically at odds with each other.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] He also said that it is an old Afghan trick to side with the winner or at least stay away from the losing side, and that is why Afghan military disintegrated so quickly.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Senior Afghan officials also sold fuel and ammunition supplies belonging to Afghan security forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The politicisation of Afghan military resulted in unqualified politicians, loyal to Ashraf Ghani, securing key positions in Afghan military.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Hamdullah Mohib, Ghani's national security adviser, took direct control of military operations despite having no military experience.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to several senior government officials and diplomats, Mohib's orders often bypassed the normal chain of command.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Experts say that there were Generals in Afghan security forces that were put in charge through connections rather than capability.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Vali Nasr blamed Ghani for "fail[ing] from day one to create a political consensus in Kabul" to resist the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Patricia Gossman, a senior Human Rights Watch researcher, told *Insider* that issues such as human rights abuses and corruption undermined state credibility in the eyes of Afghan communities and played a big role in the country's fall.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Gossman said that US and its allies had aligned themselves with notorious figures in Afghanistan who were reviled by many communities because of atrocities committed by them in the past.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Afghan leaders within the government, military, and police have been accused of crimes ranging from corruption to murder, rape, torture, and war crimes.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Asadullah Khalid, a former Afghan defense minister, was allegedly engaged in or ordered torture, sexual violence, and extrajudicial killings, according to Human Rights Watch.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Abdul Raziq Achakzai, a former Afghan National Police chief, was accused of running secret detention centers and carrying out or ordering torture and extrajudicial killings by human right organisations.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Taliban's victory was facilitated by support from Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] For example, the Haqqani Network, a Taliban affiliate based on Pakistan, had strong support from Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), the Pakistan intelligence agency.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Taliban leaders found a safe haven in Pakistan, lived in the country, transacted business and earned funds there, and receiving medical treatment there.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Some elements of the Pakistani establishment sympathized with Taliban ideology, and many Pakistan officials considered the Taliban as an asset against India.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Antonio Giustozzi, a senior research fellow at Royal United Services Institute on terrorism and conflict, wrote, "Both the Russians and the Iranians helped the Taliban advance at a breakneck pace in May–August 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Although India has not formally recognised Afghanistan's de facto rulers, it is one of a number of countries that maintain some form of diplomatic or informal relations with the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] India currently has a small mission in Kabul, and sends humanitarian aid to Afghanistan, one of the poorest countries in the world.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 9th October 2025, India announced it will reopen an Embassy in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 12 August, former US adviser Vali Nasr, said that there was "no kind of leadership that would give local warlords reasons for why they should resist the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] So the more they see the Taliban victory is inevitable, the more the victory becomes inevitable, because they just cut their own deals with them".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 23 June, the United States Intelligence Community estimated that the Afghan government could fall within the next six months following the US withdrawal.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 10 August, US officials revised the previous six month estimate, saying that it could happen much more quickly, and that some scenarios envisioned the fall of Kabul within 30 to 90 days.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 13 August, reports appeared that "senior Western diplomatic sources" expected the Taliban to enter Kabul within the next seven days.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 8 July, US President Joe Biden speaking to reporters in a press conference, said that a Taliban takeover of Afghanistan is not inevitable, stating, "the Afghan troops have 300,000 well-equipped—as well-equipped as any army in the world—and an air force against something like 75,000 Taliban".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Biden said that the US intelligence community had not assessed that the Afghan government would likely collapse.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Biden added that "...the likelihood there's going to be the Taliban overrunning everything and owning the whole country is highly unlikely".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 15 August, during the entrance of the Taliban into Kabul, diplomats and staff were evacuated from the US embassy in Kabul via US Black Hawk and Chinook helicopters.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 11 July, Pentagon press secretary John Kirby said that the ANDSF "have much more capacity than they've ever had before" and, "they know how to defend their country".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 9 August, Special Inspector General for Afghanistan Reconstruction John Sopko stated that the US military command "knew how bad the Afghan military was".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The report also found that the US prioritised internal political interests instead of Afghan interests, that it had demonstrated ignorance of local context, and had wasted billions of dollars on unsustainable and bureaucratic projects.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Former CENTCOM commander Frank McKenzie said that ultimately the responsibility lay with "the chain of command".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The initial invasion of Afghanistan, intended to disrupt Al Qaeda's networks, had ballooned into a nation building project: "an attempt to impose a form of government, a state, that would be a state the way that we recognize a state." According to McKenzie, the US "lost track of why we were there".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] One of the consequences of the declining socio-political situation in Afghanistan was the increasing migration flow of citizens.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The spillover effects of the Taliban offensive meant that thousands of civilians had started considering migrating.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] These migrants did not await the culmination of the war and started their move in the summer of 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] As the offensive was gathering pace, hundreds of Afghans in the north-east crossed across the border to Tajikistan in early July.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] By mid-July, Tajikistan reported that 1,000 civilians had crossed into its territory.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Meanwhile, the government of Pakistan, which shares a long border with Afghanistan, ruled out taking more refugees on top of the existing ones residing there.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In late July, 1,500 migrants were detained along the Iranian border.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Many others made the 1,000 mile (1,600 km) journey across Iran to cross into eastern Turkey; 200 Afghan migrants were intercepted by Turkey en route to Europe.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Turkey announced the construction of a border barrier along the Iran–Turkey border, where many refugees cross into Turkey en route to Europe.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The government of Tajikistan committed to accepting up to 100,000 Afghan refugees as reported on 23 July, several weeks before the fall of Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 7 August, Pakistan once again reported that it will not accept additional refugees, deploying its army along the border.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] When Kabul fell on 15 August, thousands of Afghans attempting to flee the country rushed to the airport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In desperation, several people clung to the side of a US military plane, falling to their deaths when the plane took off.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] US troops eventually had to fire warning shots to clear paths for the aircraft, which were evacuating Afghan government officials.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 17 August, India announced that it will issue an emergency e-visa to all Afghan nationals who want to come to the country, having "already received requests from Afghan Sikh and Hindu community leaders".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Due to the sealed India–Pakistan border however, an influx of Afghan refugees coming through Pakistan was not a concern to the Indian government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] A small number of refugees entered Nepal via the India–Nepal border.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Both Uzbekistan and Tajikistan reported that they will temporarily host Afghan refugees as of the end of August 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 5 August, six European Union (EU) member states, including Germany, urged the European Commission to continue deporting rejected asylum seekers back to Afghanistan despite major advances by Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] A few days later, Germany and the Netherlands temporarily suspended the deportation of Afghan refugees as Taliban insurgents captured more territory.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] While the Belarusian government denied this accusation, Poland called it a "hybrid attack" on the bloc and said the migrants should not be allowed entry because they are technically still in Belarus.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 13 August, the Canadian government announced that Canada will resettle more than 20,000 Afghan citizens from groups it considers likely targets of the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The United Kingdom said it will allow 20,000 Afghans to settle in the UK, and the US appears likely to relocate up to 30,000 Afghan SIV applicants into the United States.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Australia promised to resettle more than 3,000 Afghan refugees.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Germany said it will take in about 10,000 Afghans.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] More than 300,000 Afghan civilians risk Taliban retaliation because they worked for the US government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] As of 17 August, there were about 11,000 American citizens stranded in Taliban-held Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 17 August, the British government announced that it would be establishing a resettlement scheme for up to 20,000 Afghan refugees; prioritising women, children, and minorities.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 19 August, the government of Finland announced it planned to double its refugee quota to take in more from Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Philippines also expressed openness to accept refugees from Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Von der Leyen praised the initiative by Prime Minister Pedro Sánchez's government, stating that the actions of Spain represent "a good example of the European soul at its best".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] US President Joe Biden spoke with Sánchez to allow the use of Rota and Morón Air Bases to temporarily accommodate Afghan refugees, while praising "Spain's leadership in seeking international support for Afghan women and girls".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] However, some governments began indicating a hostile attitude towards refugees.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In a press conference, French president Emmanuel Macron stated that France needed to "anticipate and protect itself from a wave of migrants".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Austrian government announced that it would not suspend deportations to Afghanistan, unlike several other EU countries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Australian Minister of Defence Peter Dutton suggested in a TV interview that allowing Afghan civilians who had worked with the Australian government to claim asylum in Australia could pose a security risk and that "we don't know enough about those individuals".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The government of Uzbekistan has warned that it will suppress harshly any attempts to illegally cross its border.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] It has however opened its airport in Tashkent for refugees, who will be immediately redirected to flights to Berlin as part of its agreement with Germany.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Government of Sebastián Piñera in Chile announced it would accept about ten refugee families.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Meanwhile, the government of Colombia is planning to temporarily receive up to 4,000 Afghan nationals per request of the United States government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The US State Department issued a statement that relocation cases would be processed in third countries, citing Turkey as a possible venue.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The US had not previously discussed this possibility with Turkey.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to *Bloomberg News*, Turkey responded negatively and "blasted the US for recommending that Afghans fearful of a vengeful Taliban seek asylum in America from third countries".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] By 1 September 2021, the total number of evacuees numbered 124,334 people, while the total number of American service members and personnel killed in action were 2,461, with more than 20,000 Americans wounded in action.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] These numbers do not reflect the number of contractors and allied forces who were killed in action, nor the tens of thousands of Afghan National Security forces and civilians who lost their lives in this conflict.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Taliban also destroyed nine M1117 ASVs, four Mi-17s and three UH-60A BlackHawks, one DJI Mavic and 104 trucks, vehicles and jeeps.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Oryx only counts destroyed vehicles and equipment of which photo or videographic evidence is available.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Since 2 July, US aircraft attacked military equipment captured by the insurgents, destroying D30 howitzers, tanks, MRAPs and Humvees.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 25 August, Alexander Mikheev, the head of the Russian state exporter Rosoboronexporter, told Interfax news agency that the Taliban had captured more than 100 Mi-17 Hip helicopters of various types.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Mikheev also said that a large part of this helicopter fleet could be grounded as the fleet require repairs, maintenance and spare parts.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] *The Guardian* newspaper reported that Mikheev's estimate for the number of Russian-made helicopters in Afghanistan is significantly more than the reported inventory.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In the aftermath of the Taliban takeover, claims circulated that $85 billion worth of military equipment fell into Taliban hands.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] However, the estimated figure is inaccurate.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Total US equipment and transportation funding for the Afghanistan Security Forces Fund from the 20-year period from 2001 to 2021 is estimated at $18 billion or $24 billion.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The actual value of military equipment seized by the Taliban is significantly less, because by the time of the Taliban takeover, most of the military equipment had been used up, rendered inoperable, removed from Afghanistan, decommissioned, or destroyed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In the years and months preceding the 2021 Taliban offense, the US military had also removed a large amount of military equipment and weapons.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In the period immediately prior to the withdrawal, the US destroyed 70 MRAPs, 27 Humvees, and 73 aircraft, as well as CRAM systems and armored vehicles.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The total number of aircraft, vehicles, and other equipment seized by the Taliban is unknown, and possibly is not even known by the Taliban itself.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] It is expected that the value and utility of the equipment will decrease significantly if, as expected, the Taliban is unable to maintain the equipment or make spare parts for some of it.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Taliban does have the capacity to maintain some equipment through cannibalization, skills learned from the internet, and mechanics who choose to work for the Taliban or are coerced into doing so.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] This capability is especially relevant for ground vehicles, which are more useful to the Taliban than the leftover aircraft.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Taliban also lacks the technical expertise to operate some captured equipment.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] For example, the Taliban lack trained pilots capable of operating Black Hawk helicopters, and likely also lack the expertise to operate some military encrypted radios and anti-IED jamming devices.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On the other hand, the Taliban has used US-made small arms such as M16s and M4s, and could also train pilots to operate fixed-wing C-208s, PC-12s, and A-29s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Former US Army General Joseph Votel said that the majority of the captured equipment was not equipped with any sensitive US technology.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Ben Wallace, UK defence minister, expressed concern that Taliban could sell the military equipment to shadowy mercenaries, such as the Wagner Group.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In September, images shared online on social media showed Iranian army trucks transporting US armored vehicles, which allegedly belonged to the Afghan army before the Taliban takeover, on a highway connecting the central city of Semnan to the city of Garmsar, southeast of the capital Tehran.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The vehicles included Humvees and heavily armored mine-resistant vehicles.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] A social media channel also claimed that Iran has taken possession of some US tanks.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Female MPs have gone into hiding since the offensive.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] After the fall of Kabul, former Northern Alliance members and anti-Taliban figures formed a military alliance called the National Resistance Front of Afghanistan, under the leadership of Ahmad Massoud and former Vice President Amrullah Saleh.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] They have based themselves in the Panjshir Valley, which was a major base of operations for the original Northern Alliance.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 17 August 2021, Afghan Vice President Amrullah Saleh declared himself caretaker President of Afghanistan in Panjshir Valley.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] With the fall of Kabul, former Northern Alliance members and other anti-Taliban forces based in Panjshir, led by Ahmad Massoud and former Vice President Amrullah Saleh, became the primary organized resistance to the Taliban in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 1 September, talks broke down and fighting resumed as the Taliban attacked resistance positions.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 6 September, the Taliban took full control of the Panjshir province, with resistance fighters retreating to the mountains to continue fighting within the province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] As of 3 September 2021, in addition to the opposition in the Panjshir, there are also districts in the centre of Afghanistan that are still in resistance against the Taliban, supported by ethnic and religious minorities.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] (left) with the traditional black-red-green colors, with their own white flag (right).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The traditional flag became a symbol for resistance during anti-Taliban protests.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 17 August, a small protest was held by several women in Kabul demanding equal rights for women, the first reported women's protest against the new regime.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 18 August, larger protests also attended by men emerged in three eastern Pashtun-dominated cities: Jalalabad, Khost, and Asadabad, with protestors waving the flag of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, and taking down the Taliban flag.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In Jalalabad, the Taliban opened fire, killing three and wounding over a dozen.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 19 August, demonstrations spread to various parts of Kabul, including one large protest near Kabul Airport where cars and people waved the flag of the republic, and another with over 200 people gathered near the presidential palace in Kabul before it was violently dispersed by the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Protests continued in Khost and Asadabad as well, with the Taliban using violence to disperse protests in both.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In Asadabad, protests were reported as swelling to the hundreds.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] More than three weeks after the fall of Kabul, the new Taliban rulers announced the creation of a government cabinet for the new state named Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The cabinet is all male, and is heavily dominated by ethnic Pashtuns, with only three members being of other ethnicity.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Hasan Akhund was named acting prime minister.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] As of January 2024, the cabinet officially remains in an interim state over two years after its formation.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] In July 2025, Russia became the first country to internationally recognize the Taliban government, while the governments of China, the United Arab Emirates, Uzbekistan and Pakistan all have accredited ambassadors to the Islamic Emirate.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Additionally, the Chinese government has accepted credentials of the Taliban's ambassador to Beijing, while in 2022 the Turkish foreign minister Mevlüt Çavuşoğlu expressed the intention to internationally recognize the Islamic Emirate.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Violence in the country sharply declined in the year after the Taliban takeover of Kabul, with conflict-related deaths falling by 91% for the year 2022 compared to 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Tourist numbers in post-war Afghanistan have increased by 120% in the year 2023 compared to 2022.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The service sector, making up almost half of the country's economy, fell by 30% in 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Within two years of the Taliban's victory, the overall economy of Afghanistan had contracted by 25%.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to Gallup polls, the number of Afghans struggling to afford commodities or struggling to find work has increased after the events of 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Opium cultivation has dropped by 95% between 2022 and 2023 following an enforced ban by the new Taliban administration.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Some Afghan politicians closely associated with the US-backed Afghan government, including Gul Agha Sherzai, the former governor of Nangahar province, congratulated Taliban on their victory.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Iran's president, Ebrahim Raisi, said that the 'defeat' of United States in Afghanistan should offer an opportunity to "revive life, security and lasting peace" in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Raisi also said that Iran wanted good relations with Afghanistan and that Iran is closely monitoring the situation in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Pakistan's National Security Committee (NSC) reiterated that Pakistan wants an inclusive form of political settlement in Afghanistan which represents all Afghan ethnic groups.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The committee also reaffirmed that Pakistan would continue to work with the international community and all Afghan stakeholders to facilitate an inclusive political settlement in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Pakistani foreign minister stated "concern over the deteriorating situation in Afghanistan" but said that Pakistan has no intention to close its embassy in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] His remarks were criticized (with critics pointing out that Khan himself was foreign educated) and Khan said his remarks were taken out of context.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Inter-Services Intelligence's (ISI) chief Faiz Hameed visited Kabul and met with Taliban leadership as well as other Afghan leaders including former prime minister Gulbuddin Hekmatyar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The meeting was seen as an unconventional means of contact between the two countries in the absence of a government in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The visit was purportedly to get berths for the Haqqanis in the new Government, demonstrating their, "clout" over the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, the Inter-Services Intelligence Directorate shares an undeniable link with the Taliban, especially the Haqqani group.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] United States president Joe Biden stated that he either had to stick to the deal his predecessor made with the Taliban and continue to pull out or send in more troops and risk their lives.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Chinese state-run tabloid *Global Times* blamed the United States and its allies for what they called "the disaster in Afghanistan".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The Communist Party's *People's Daily* flatteringly credited the Taliban's victory to its supposed adoption of Mao Zedong's "people's war" tactic: rallying the support of the rural population, while drawing the enemy deep into the countryside.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Russia's UN representative stated that it is time for national reconciliation, with law and order returning to the streets and of "the ending of many years of bloodshed".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Russian President, Vladimir Putin said, "It's important not to allow terrorists to spill into neighbouring countries".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Zamir Kabulov, President Putin's special envoy to Afghanistan, said the Taliban were easier to negotiate with than the old "puppet government" of exiled President Ashraf Ghani.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 14 September, the European Parliament passed a resolution deploring the Taliban for taking over Afghanistan via force of arms, failure to uphold promises for an inclusive government, not respecting human rights and freedoms of the Afghan people, and for fighting the NRF.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] According to a US defense official, the security vacuum left by the withdrawal of US military forces could create an opening for al-Qaeda and other terrorist groups to reorganize.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The official added that, while the US would still maintain authority to strike al-Qaeda targets in Afghanistan, the lack of a robust US presence on the ground would hamper the ability to identify potential targets.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] McKenzie Jr. said that he has not seen anything that would make him believe the Taliban would stop al-Qaeda from using Afghanistan to strengthen and rebuild.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] British Defence Secretary Ben Wallace said that the vacuum could give terrorist groups like al-Qaeda another chance for a safe haven.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] On 8 August, the head of extremist monitoring group SITE, Rita Katz, said that the Taliban advance resembled the earlier days of the Syrian civil war amid al-Nusra Front's victories, "except now on a completely different scale, given the Taliban's horrifying momentum".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] Kazakh political scientist Dosym Satpaev warned that a Taliban takeover could possibly pave a way for other fundamental Islamist forces in an attempt to form a merger state of Central Asia and Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] After the Taliban seizure of Afghanistan, *The Hindu* claimed that many Jaish-e-Mohammed (JeM) cadres were released, the JeM and Taliban have held meetings and the JeM has been assured of all support in carrying out its terrorist activities in India.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] However, Taliban spokesman Zabiullah Mujahid, in an interview with India Today denied any meeting taking place between Taliban and JeM leadership.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/2021-taliban-offensive-p02] The spokesman also said that Taliban will not allow Afghanistan to be used against India or any other countries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-national-cricket-captains] This is a list of all cricketers who have captained Afghanistan in an official international match.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-national-cricket-captains] This includes the ICC Trophy, Under-19 games and One Day International.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-national-cricket-captains] This is a list of cricketers who have captained the Afghanistan cricket team for at least one Test match.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-national-cricket-captains] A cricketer who has a symbol of next to a Test match series describes their role as captain and their participation in at least one game for the team.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-national-cricket-captains] Afghanistan played their first ODI on April 19, 2009.The table of results is complete up to the third ODI against Sri Lanka in November 2022.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-national-cricket-captains] Afghanistan played their first T20I on February 1, 2010.The table of results is complete up to the third T20I against Pakistan in March 2023.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] Australian cricketer Mel Jones facilitated the fleeing of members of the Afghanistan women's national cricket team from their country in 2021 following the Fall of Kabul to the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] Former national team players have eventually been able to settle in Australia, mostly in Melbourne and Canberra.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] The women's national team under the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) was effectively disbanded while the men's national team was retained.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] Afghanistan remains a full member of the International Cricket Council (ICC), despite the requirement to maintain a women's national team.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] This was despite the Afghanistan Cricket Board not distributing ICC funding for the development of women's cricket.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] In June 2024, the women's players wrote to the ICC asking for permission to form an international refugees team.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] Due to receiving no response to their letter, in January 2025, the Afghan women refugees formerly contracted with the ACB formed a team under the name "Afghan Women's XI".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] They played their first match against Cricket Without Borders Charity XI on 30 January 2025 at the Junction Oval in Melbourne.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghan-women-s-xi] In April 2025, the ICC announced that they would be supporting Afghan women's cricket, with the 25 ACB contracted players of the Afghan Women's XI being viewed as the first potential beneficiaries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] The **Afghanistan A cricket team** is a national cricket team representing Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] It is the 'second-tier' of international Afghan cricket, below the full Afghanistan national cricket team.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] Matches played by Afghanistan A are not considered to be One Day Internationals, instead receiving List A classification.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] Their first match was against the Tajikistan national cricket team in December 2013.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] In 2017, they played a five-match series against the Zimbabwe A cricket team in Zimbabwe.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] In July 2017, they were added to the South Africa A Team Tri-Series, after Australia A withdrew.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] They toured Bangladesh in July 2019, playing two first-class and five 50-over matches against Bangladesh A.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] In October 2024, the Afghanistan A team played in the ACC emerging team asia cup tournament where they won matches against Sri Lanka and Bangladesh A but lost against Honk Kong A.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] However they won against India A in the semi final by scoring the highest ever total in the tournament history of 206.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] 2024 ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup final was played between Afghanistan A and Sri Lanka A Team on 27 October 2024 which Afghanistan A won and won their first title as such.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The **Afghanistan Cricket Board** (**ACB**; Pashto: د افغانستان کرکټ بورډ, Persian: کرکت بورد افغانستان; formerly **Afghanistan Cricket Federation**) is the official governing body of cricket in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] It is Afghanistan's representative at the International Cricket Council (ICC) and was an associate member of ICC from June 2013 until becoming a full member in June 2017.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Before that it was an affiliate member and has been a member of that body since 2001.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] It is also a member of the Asian Cricket Council.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Cricket in Afghanistan was first played during the 19th century Anglo-Afghan Wars, with British troops reported as having played in Kabul in 1839.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] However, unlike many countries, no lasting cricket legacy was left by the British, and it would be more than a hundred years before cricket returned.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] In the 1990s, cricket became popular amongst Afghan refugees in Pakistan, and the Afghanistan Cricket Federation was formed there in 1995.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] They continued to play cricket on their return to their home country in late 2001.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Like all sports, cricket was originally banned by the ruling Taliban, but it became a notable exception in 2000 and the Afghanistan Cricket Federation was elected as an affiliate member of the ICC the following year.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The Afghanistan national cricket team's 21-run win over Namibia in Krugersdorp earned them official One Day International status in April 2009.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The team qualified for the 2012 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] On 11 November 2010, the Afghanistan women's national cricket team was formed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] This was intended to help women understand the game of cricket and have a parallel team to that of the men.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The team folded in 2014 due to a lack of support from the ACB, as well as threats from the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] An attempt at reforming the team was made in 2020, but all 25 players were forced to flee the country when the Taliban took control of Afghanistan in 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] As of 2024, the ACB has no plans to reform a women's side, and has avoided contact with the players who fled the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] In July 2016, ACB unveiled a strategic plan and set targets for Afghanistan to be a top-six ODI team by 2019 and a top-three team in both T20Is and ODIs by 2025.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] In order to achieve this, ACB created a proposal to be presented to BCCI, in the works to secure annual bilateral matches against India and teams touring India beginning next year.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Shafiq Stanikzai, Chief Executive of ACB, said the draft had been presented to BCCI president Anurag Thakur in May and further discussions had happened during the ICC Annual Conference in Edinburgh in June 2016.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] On 22 June 2017, Afghanistan was granted Test nation status by the ICC.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] This was the first time in history that two teams earned test status at the same time.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Afghanistan share this honour with Ireland, thus bringing the number of total number of test playing nations to twelve.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] On 14 June 2018, they played their first test match against India, which they lost within two days.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] In August 2021, Taliban leaders arrived to the ACB headquarters accompanied by former Afghan national cricketer Abdullah Mazari, and ordered the cricket board to carry on the activities as usual.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Afghanistan's domestic structure consisted of a 25-over Inter-Provincial Tournament, which had the participation of 22 provinces in the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The aim of the tournament was to spread the game across the country and to generate a greater depth of talent for the national team to select from.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The best players from the tournament were selected for Afghanistan-A and under-19 teams based on their performance and would be sent for training and coaching to Bangladesh.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Afghanistan teams often visit Pakistan.In February 2013, the Afghanistan national cricket team traveled to Pakistan for a series of List A and T20 matches.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Two teams from the 12-team first round will advance to the next round.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The top six from the tournament will then contest Afghanistan's main domestic event - a 50 over tournament in Kabul in May 2010.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The 50 over tournament was won by Kabul Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Starting in 2011, Afghanistan's domestic cricket structure has grown.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The expanded Inter-Provincial Tournament was reorganized into a 50 over tournament and divided into a Challenge Cup section (the Etisalat ODN Challenge Cup with 20 provincial teams) and an Elite Cup section (with 12 provincial teams; 4 of them qualifiers from the Challenge Cup section).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] In addition to the Inter-Provincial cricket the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) has divided the provinces of Afghanistan into 5 Cricket Regions to enable the better management of the game.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The Regions are Amo in the north (centered on Balkh), Spin Ghar in the east (centered on Nangarhar), Band-e-Amir in the centre (centered on Kabul), Mis Ainak in the southeast (centered on Khost), and Boost in the west and southwest (centered on Kandahar).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The 5 regions in turn have representative teams which play in all traditional 3 formats of cricket; the Ahmad Shah Abdali One-Day Tournament, Ahmad Shah Abdali T20 Tournament and Ahmad Shah Abdali 4-day Tournament.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] There are also plans to expand the three-day league competition into a four-day league in 2014.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The Afghan national cricket team does not play its home matches inside Afghanistan due to the ongoing security situation and the lack of international standard facilities.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Afghanistan played their 'home' Intercontinental Cup fixture against Ireland at the Rangiri Dambulla International Stadium in Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Following Afghanistan's World Twenty20 qualifying campaign they played two One-Day Internationals against Canada at the Sharjah Cricket Association Stadium in the UAE, after which the stadium was named the 'home' ground of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The President of the Afghanistan Cricket Board, Omar Zakhilwal, announced in October 2010 that the government was planning to construct standard cricket grounds in all 34 provinces in the next two years.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] In January 2021, the Afghanistan Cricket Board made announcement of exploring the possibility of using Oman as a new 'home' venue for international cricket matches.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The Afghanistan national cricket team represents the country of Afghanistan in international cricket matches.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The national team was formed in 2001, which played in the 2009 World Cup Qualifier after rising rapidly through the World Cricket League, starting in Division Five in May 2008.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] They play in the Elite division of the ACC Trophy.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Afghanistan's 21-run win over Namibia in Krugersdorp earned them official One Day International status.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Afghanistan won their first One Day International against Scotland.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] In 2011, the team qualified for the 2012 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Afghanistan played its first 50 over World Cup in 2015.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] It played 6 matches in all and won 1 match (against Scotland) and losing the rest.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] They also qualified for ICC World T20-2016.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] In December 2015, Afghanistan hired the services of Manoj Prabhakar, the former Indian all rounder as their bowling coach.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] The Afghanistan Cricket Board previously attempted to form a women's national cricket team which was first organized in 2010.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] Due to the Taliban takeover of Afghanistan, all 25 players were forced to flee the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-cricket-board] As of 2024, there are no plans for the ACB to reform the team.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Human habitation in Afghanistan dates to the Middle Paleolithic era.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Popularly referred to as the graveyard of empires, the land has witnessed numerous military campaigns, including those by the Persians, Alexander the Great, the Maurya Empire, Arab Muslims, the Mongols, the British, the Soviet Union, and a US-led coalition.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan also served as the source from which the Greco-Bactrians and the Mughals, among others, rose to form major empires.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Because of the various conquests and periods in both the Iranian and Indian cultural spheres, the area was a center for Zoroastrianism, Buddhism, Hinduism, and later Islam.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The modern state of Afghanistan began with the Durrani Empire in the 18th century under Ahmad Shah Durrani, although Dost Mohammad Khan is sometimes considered to be the founder of the first modern Afghan state.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan became a buffer state in the Great Game between the British Empire and the Russian Empire.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] From India, the British attempted to subjugate Afghanistan but were repelled in the First Anglo-Afghan War; the Second Anglo-Afghan War saw a British victory.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Following the Third Anglo-Afghan War in 1919, Afghanistan became free of foreign political hegemony, and emerged as the independent Kingdom of Afghanistan in 1926; this monarchy lasted almost half a century.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Since the late 1970s, Afghanistan's history has been dominated by extensive warfare, including coups, invasions, insurgencies, and civil wars.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] This period of instability began in 1973 when King Zahir Shah was overthrown by his cousin Mohammad Daoud Khan, ending the monarchy and resulting in the establishment of the Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan became the President of Afghanistan, ruling as an autocrat.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In 1978 the conflict became a violent one when a communist revolution overthrew and assassinated Daoud Khan, establishing the socialist Democratic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Subsequent infighting prompted the Soviet Union to invade Afghanistan in 1979.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The *mujahideen* won against the Soviets in the Soviet–Afghan War, leading to the Soviets' withdrawal in 1989.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The ensuing civil war overthrew the socialist republic and established the Islamic State of Afghanistan through the Peshawar Accord, which could not remain in force and resulted in a second civil war between *mujahideen* factions in 1992.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban controlled most of the country by 1996, but their Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan received little international recognition before its overthrow in the 2001 US invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban returned to power in 2021 after capturing Kabul, ending the 2001–2021 war.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is widely unrecognized by the international community due to reported violations of human rights in Afghanistan, particularly regarding the treatment of women by the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is rich in natural resources, including lithium, iron, zinc, and copper.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] It is the third largest producer of both saffron and cashmere.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The country is a member of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation and a founding member of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Due to the effects of war in recent decades, the country has dealt with high levels of terrorism, poverty, and child malnutrition.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remains among the world's least developed countries with its economic output per capita among the lowest of any country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Some scholars suggest that the root name *Afghān* is derived from the Sanskrit word *Aśvakan*, which was the name used for ancient inhabitants of the Hindu Kush.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] *Aśvakan* literally means "horsemen", "horse breeders", or "cavalrymen" (from *aśva*, the Sanskrit and Avestan words for "horse").
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Historically, the ethnonym *Afghān* was used to refer to ethnic Pashtuns.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Arabic and Persian form of the name, *Afġān*, was first attested in the 10th-century geography book *Hudud al-'Alam*.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The last part of the name, "*-stan*", is a Persian suffix meaning "place of".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Therefore, "Afghanistan" translates to "land of the Afghans", or "land of the Pashtuns" in a historical sense.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The term "Afghanistan" was officially used in 1855, when the British recognized Dost Mohammad Khan as king of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Excavations of prehistoric sites suggest that humans were living in what is now Afghanistan at least 50,000 years ago, and that farming communities in the area were among the earliest in the world.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] An important site of early historical activities, many believe that Afghanistan compares to Egypt in the historical value of its archaeological sites.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Artifacts typical of the Paleolithic, Mesolithic, Neolithic, Bronze, and Iron Ages have been found in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Urban civilization is believed to have begun as early as 3000 BCE, and the early city of Mundigak (near Kandahar in the south of the country) was a center of the Helmand culture.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] More recent findings established that the Indus Valley Civilization stretched up towards modern-day Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] An Indus Valley site has been found on the Oxus River at Shortugai in northern Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] After 2000 BCE successive waves of semi-nomadic people from Central Asia began moving south into Afghanistan; among them were many Indo-European-speaking Indo-Iranians.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] These tribes later migrated further into South Asia, Western Asia, and toward Europe via the area north of the Caspian Sea.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The region at the time was referred to as Ariana.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] By the middle of the 6th century BCE, the Achaemenids overthrew the Medes and incorporated Arachosia, Aria, and Bactria within its eastern boundaries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] An inscription on the tombstone of Darius I of Persia mentions the Kabul Valley in a list of the 29 countries that he had conquered.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The region of Arachosia, around Kandahar in modern-day southern Afghanistan, used to be primarily Zoroastrian and played a key role in the transfer of the Avesta to Persia and is thus considered by some to be the "second homeland of Zoroastrianism".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Alexander the Great and his Macedonian forces arrived in Afghanistan in 330 BCE after defeating Darius III of Persia a year earlier in the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Following Alexander's brief occupation, the successor state of the Seleucid Empire controlled the region until 305 BCE, when they gave much of it to the Maurya Empire as part of an alliance treaty.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Mauryans controlled the area south of the Hindu Kush until they were overthrown in about 185 BCE.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Their decline began 60 years after Ashoka's rule ended, leading to the Hellenistic reconquest by the Greco-Bactrians.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Much of it soon broke away and became part of the Indo-Greek Kingdom.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] They were defeated and expelled by the Indo-Scythians in the late 2nd century BCE.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Silk Road appeared during the first century BCE, and Afghanistan flourished with trade, with routes to China, India, Persia, and north to the cities of Bukhara, Samarkand, and Khiva in present-day Uzbekistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Goods and ideas were exchanged at this center point, such as Chinese silk, Persian silver and Roman gold, while the region of present Afghanistan was mining and trading lapis lazuli stones mainly from the Badakhshan region.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] During the first century BCE, the Parthian Empire subjugated the region but lost it to their Indo-Parthian vassals.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In the mid-to-late first century CE the vast Kushan Empire, centered in Afghanistan, became great patrons of Buddhist culture, making Buddhism flourish throughout the region.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Kushans were overthrown by the Sassanids in the 3rd century CE, though the Indo-Sassanids continued to rule at least parts of the region.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] They were followed by the Kidarites who, in turn, was replaced by the Hephthalites.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] They were replaced by the Turk Shahi in the 7th century.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Buddhist Turk Shahi of Kabul was replaced by a Hindu dynasty before the Saffarids conquered the area in 870; this Hindu dynasty was called Hindu Shahi.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Much of the northeastern and southern areas of the country remained dominated by Buddhist culture.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Arab Muslims brought Islam to Herat and Zaranj in 642 CE and began spreading eastward; some of the native inhabitants they encountered accepted it while others revolted.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Before the arrival of Islam, the region used to be home to various beliefs and cults, often resulting in Syncretism between the dominant religions such as Zoroastrianism, Buddhism or Greco-Buddhism, Ancient Iranian religions, Hinduism, Christianity, and Judaism.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] An exemplification of the syncretism in the region would be that people were patrons of Buddhism but still worshipped local Iranian gods such as Ahura Mazda, Lady Nana, Anahita or Mihr (Mithra) and portrayed Greek gods as protectors of Buddha.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Zunbils and Kabul Shahi were first conquered in 870 CE by the Saffarid Muslims of Zaranj.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Later, the Samanids extended their Islamic influence south of the Hindu Kush.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavids rose to power in the 10th century.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] By the 11th century, Mahmud of Ghazni had defeated the remaining Hindu rulers and effectively Islamized the wider region, with the exception of Kafiristan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud made Ghazni into an important city and patronized intellectuals such as the historian al-Biruni and the poet Ferdowsi.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavid dynasty was overthrown by the Ghurids in 1186, whose architectural achievements included the remote Minaret of Jam.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Ghurids controlled Afghanistan for less than a century before being conquered by the Khwarazmian dynasty in 1215.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In 1219 CE, Genghis Khan and his Mongol army overran the region.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] His troops are said to have annihilated the Khwarazmian cities of Herat and Balkh as well as Bamyan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The destruction caused by the Mongols forced many locals to return to an agrarian rural society.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Mongol rule continued with the Ilkhanate in the northwest while the Khalji dynasty administered the Afghan tribal areas south of the Hindu Kush until the invasion of Timur (aka Tamerlane), who established the Timurid Empire in 1370.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Under the rule of Shah Rukh, the city of Herat served as the focal point of the Timurid Renaissance, whose glory matched Florence of the Italian Renaissance as the center of a cultural rebirth.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In the early 16th century Babur arrived from Ferghana and captured Kabul from the Arghun dynasty.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Babur would go on to conquer the Afghan Lodi dynasty who had ruled the Delhi Sultanate in the First Battle of Panipat.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Between the 16th and 18th century, the Uzbek Khanate of Bukhara, Iranian Safavids, and Indian Mughals ruled parts of the territory.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] During the medieval period, the northwestern area of Afghanistan was referred to by the regional name Khorasan, which was commonly used up to the 19th century among natives to describe their country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In 1709, Mirwais Hotak, a local Ghilzai tribal leader, successfully rebelled against the Safavids.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He defeated Gurgin Khan, the Georgian governor of Kandahar under the Safavids, and established his own kingdom.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Mirwais died in 1715, and was succeeded by his brother Abdul Aziz, who was soon killed by Mirwais's son Mahmud for possibly planning to sign a peace with the Safavids.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud led the Afghan army in 1722 to the Persian capital of Isfahan, and captured the city after the Battle of Gulnabad and proclaimed himself King of Persia.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan dynasty was ousted from Persia by Nader Shah after the 1729 Battle of Damghan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In 1738, Nader Shah and his forces captured Kandahar in the siege of Kandahar, the last Hotak stronghold, from Shah Hussain Hotak.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Soon after, the Persian and Afghan forces invaded India, Nader Shah had plundered Delhi, alongside his 16-year-old commander, Ahmad Shah Durrani who had assisted him on these campaigns.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Ahmad Shah had launched two campaigns into Khorasan, 1750–1751 and 1754–1755.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] By the early 19th century, the Afghan empire was under threat from the Persians in the west and the Sikh Empire in the east.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan, leader of the Barakzai tribe, installed many of his brothers in positions of power throughout the empire.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan was brutally murdered in 1818 by Mahmud Shah.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] As a result, the brothers of Fateh Khan and the Barakzai tribe rebelled, and a civil war brewed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] During this turbulent period, Afghanistan fractured into many states, including the Principality of Qandahar, Emirate of Herat, Khanate of Qunduz, Maimana Khanate, and numerous other warring polities.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The most prominent state was the Emirate of Kabul, ruled by Dost Mohammad Khan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Akbar Khan and the Afghan army failed to capture the Jamrud Fort from the Sikh Khalsa Army, but killed Sikh commander Hari Singh Nalwa, thus ending the Afghan-Sikh Wars.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In 1893, Abdur Rahman signed an agreement in which the ethnic Pashtun and Baloch territories were divided by the Durand Line, which forms the modern-day border between Pakistan and Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Shia-dominated Hazarajat and pagan Kafiristan remained politically independent until being conquered by Abdur Rahman Khan in 1891–1896.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He was known as the "Iron Amir" for his features and his ruthless methods against tribes.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He died in 1901, succeeded by his son, Habibullah Khan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] During the First World War, when Afghanistan was neutral, Habibullah Khan was met by officials of the Central Powers in the Niedermayer–Hentig Expedition.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] They called on Afghanistan to declare full independence from the United Kingdom, join them and attack British India, as part of the Hindu–German Conspiracy.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The effort to bring Afghanistan into the Central Powers failed, but it sparked discontent among the population about maintaining neutrality with the British.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Habibullah was assassinated in February 1919, and Amanullah Khan eventually assumed power.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] A staunch supporter of the 1915–1916 expeditions, Amanullah Khan invaded British India, beginning the Third Anglo-Afghan War, and entering British India via the Khyber Pass.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Following the end of the Third Anglo-Afghan War and the signing of the Treaty of Rawalpindi on 19 August 1919, Emir Amanullah Khan declared the Emirate of Afghanistan a sovereign and fully independent state.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He moved to end his country's traditional isolation by establishing diplomatic relations with the international community, particularly with the Soviet Union and the Weimar Republic.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He proclaimed himself King of Afghanistan on 9 June 1926, forming the Kingdom of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He introduced several reforms intended to modernize his nation.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] A key force behind these reforms was Mahmud Tarzi, an ardent supporter of the education of women.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He fought for Article 68 of Afghanistan's 1923 constitution, which implemented compulsory elementary education.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah's wife, Queen Soraya, was an important figure during this period in the fight for women's education and against their oppression.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Some of the reforms, such as the abolition of the traditional burqa for women and the opening of co-educational schools, alienated many tribal and religious leaders, leading to the Afghan Civil War (1928–1929).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah abdicated in January 1929, and soon after Kabul fell to Saqqawist forces led by Habibullah Kalakani.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Mohammad Nadir Shah, Amanullah's cousin, defeated and killed Kalakani in October 1929, and was declared King Nadir Shah.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He abandoned the reforms of King Amanullah in favor of a more gradual approach to modernization, but was assassinated in 1933 by Abdul Khaliq.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Mohammed Zahir Shah succeeded to the throne and reigned as king from 1933 to 1973.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] During the tribal revolts of 1944–1947, King Zahir's reign was challenged by Zadran, Safi, Mangal, and Wazir tribesmen led by Mazrak Zadran, Salemai, and Faqir of Ipi, among others – many of whom were Amanullah loyalists.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan joined the League of Nations in 1934.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In the 1930s, the country experienced significant development of roads, infrastructure, the founding of a national bank, and increased education.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Road links in the north played a large part in a growing cotton and textile industry.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The country built close relationships with the Axis powers, with Nazi Germany having the largest share in Afghan development at the time.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Until 1946, King Zahir ruled with the assistance of his uncle, who held the post of prime minister and continued the policies of Nadir Shah.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Another uncle, Shah Mahmud Khan, became prime minister in 1946 and experimented with allowing greater political freedom.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] He was replaced in 1953 by Mohammed Daoud Khan, a Pashtun nationalist who sought the creation of a Pashtunistan, leading to highly tense relations with Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan pressed for social modernization reforms and sought a closer relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afterward, the 1964 constitution was formed, and the first non-royal prime minister was sworn in.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Zahir Shah, like his father Nadir Shah, had a policy of maintaining national independence while pursuing gradual modernization, creating nationalist feeling, and improving relations with the United Kingdom.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan was neither a participant in World War II nor aligned with either power bloc in the Cold War.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] However, it was a beneficiary of the latter rivalry as both the Soviet Union and the United States vied for influence by building Afghanistan's main highways, airports, and other vital infrastructure.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] On a per capita basis, Afghanistan received more Soviet development aid than any other country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In 1973, while the King was in Italy, Daoud Khan launched a bloodless coup and became the first president of Afghanistan, abolishing the monarchy.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In April 1978, the communist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA) seized power in a bloody coup d'état against then-President Mohammed Daoud Khan, in what is called the Saur Revolution.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA declared the establishment of the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan, with its first leader named as People's Democratic Party General Secretary Nur Muhammad Taraki.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] This would trigger a series of events that would dramatically turn Afghanistan from a peaceful (albeit poor and secluded) country to a hotbed of conflict and terrorism.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA initiated various social, symbolic, and land distribution reforms that provoked strong opposition, while also brutally oppressing political dissidents.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] This caused unrest and quickly expanded into a state of civil war by 1979, waged by guerrilla *mujahideen* (and smaller Maoist guerrillas) against regime forces countrywide.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] It quickly turned into a proxy war as the Pakistani government provided these rebels with covert training centers, the United States supported them through Pakistan's Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), and the Soviet Union sent thousands of military advisers to support the PDPA regime.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Meanwhile, there was increasingly hostile friction between the competing factions of the PDPA – the dominant Khalq and the more moderate Parcham.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In October 1979, PDPA General Secretary Taraki was assassinated in an internal coup orchestrated by then-prime minister Hafizullah Amin, who became the new general secretary of the PDPA.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The situation in the country deteriorated under Amin, and thousands of people went missing.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Displeased with Amin's government, the Soviet Army invaded the country in December 1979, heading for Kabul and killing Amin.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] A Soviet-organized regime, led by Parcham's Babrak Karmal but inclusive of both factions (Parcham and Khalq), filled the vacuum.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Soviet troops in more substantial numbers were deployed to stabilize Afghanistan under Karmal, marking the beginning of the Soviet–Afghan War.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Lasting nine years, the war caused the deaths of between 562,000 and 2 million Afghans, and displaced about 6 million people who subsequently fled Afghanistan, mainly to Pakistan and Iran.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Heavy air bombardment destroyed many countryside villages, millions of landmines were planted, and some cities such as Herat and Kandahar were also damaged from bombardment.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] After the Soviet withdrawal, another civil war ensued until the communist regime under PDPA leader Mohammad Najibullah collapsed in 1992.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Soviet–Afghan War had drastic social effects on Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The militarization of society led to heavily armed police, private bodyguards, openly armed civil defense groups, and the like becoming the norm in Afghanistan for decades thereafter.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The traditional power structure had shifted from the clergy, community elders, intelligentsia, and military in favor of powerful warlords.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Another civil war broke out after the creation of a dysfunctional coalition government between leaders of various *mujahideen* factions.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Amid a state of anarchy and factional infighting, various *mujahideen* factions committed widespread rape, murder, and extortion, while Kabul was heavily bombarded and partially destroyed by the fighting.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Several failed reconciliations and alliances occurred between different leaders.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban emerged in September 1994 as a movement and militia of students (*talib*) from Islamic madrassas (schools) in Pakistan, who soon had military support from Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Taking control of Kandahar city that year, they conquered more territories until finally driving out the government of Rabbani from Kabul in 1996, where they established an emirate.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban were condemned internationally for the harsh enforcement of their interpretation of Islamic sharia law, which resulted in the brutal treatment of many Afghans, especially women.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] During their rule, the Taliban and their allies committed massacres against Afghan civilians, denied UN food supplies to starving civilians, and conducted a policy of scorched earth, burning vast areas of fertile land and destroying tens of thousands of homes.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] After the fall of Kabul to the Taliban, Ahmad Shah Massoud and Abdul Rashid Dostum formed the Northern Alliance, later joined by others, to resist the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Dostum's forces were defeated by the Taliban during the Battles of Mazar-i-Sharif in 1997 and 1998; Pakistan's Chief of Army Staff, Pervez Musharraf, began sending thousands of Pakistani militants to help the Taliban defeat the Northern Alliance.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] By 2000, the Northern Alliance only controlled 10% of the territory, cornered in the northeast.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] On 9 September 2001, Massoud was assassinated by two Arab suicide attackers in Panjshir Valley.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Around 400,000 Afghans died in internal conflicts between 1990 and 2001.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In October 2001, the United States invaded Afghanistan to remove the Taliban from power after they refused to hand over Osama bin Laden, the prime suspect of the September 11 attacks, who was a "guest" of the Taliban and was operating his al-Qaeda network in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The majority of Afghans supported the American invasion.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] During the initial invasion, US and UK forces bombed al-Qaeda training camps, and later, in cooperation with the Northern Alliance, the Taliban regime came to an end.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In December 2001, after the Taliban government was overthrown, the Afghan Interim Administration under Hamid Karzai was formed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) was established by the United Nations Security Council to assist the Karzai administration and provide basic security.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] By this time, after two decades of war as well as an acute famine at the time, Afghanistan had one of the highest infant and child mortality rates in the world, the lowest life expectancy, much of the population suffered from hunger and malnutrition, and infrastructure was in ruins.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Many foreign donors started providing aid and assistance to rebuild the war-torn country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] As coalition troops entered Afghanistan to help the rebuilding process, the Taliban began an insurgency to regain control.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remained one of the poorest countries in the world because of a lack of foreign investment, government corruption, and the Taliban insurgency.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan government was able to establish some democratic structures, adopting a constitution in 2004 with the name Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Attempts were made, often with the support of foreign donor countries, to improve the country's economy, healthcare, education, transport, and agriculture.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] ISAF forces also began to train the Afghan National Security Forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Following 2002, nearly five million Afghans were repatriated.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The number of NATO troops present in Afghanistan peaked at 140,000 in 2011, dropping to approximately 16,000 in 2018.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In September 2014, Ashraf Ghani became president after the 2014 Afghan presidential election, in which, for the first time in Afghanistan's history, power was democratically transferred.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] On 28 December 2014, NATO formally ended ISAF combat operations and transferred full security responsibility to the Afghan government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The NATO-led Operation Resolute Support was formed the same day as a successor to ISAF.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Thousands of NATO troops remained in the country to train and advise Afghan government forces and continue their fight against the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] A report titled *Body Count* concluded that 106,000–170,000 civilians had been killed as a result of the fighting in Afghanistan at the hands of all parties to the conflict.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] On 19 February 2020, the United States–Taliban deal was made in Qatar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg announced on 14 April 2021 that the alliance had agreed to start withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan by 1 May.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Soon after NATO troops began withdrawing, the Taliban launched an offensive against the Afghan government and quickly advanced in front of collapsing Afghan government forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban captured the capital city of Kabul on 15 August 2021, after regaining control over a vast majority of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Several foreign diplomats and Afghan government officials, including President Ashraf Ghani, were evacuated from the country, with many Afghan civilians attempting to flee along with them.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] On 17 August, first vice president Amrullah Saleh proclaimed himself caretaker president and announced the formation of an anti-Taliban front with a reported 6,000+ troops in the Panjshir Valley, along with Ahmad Massoud.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] However, by 6 September, the Taliban had taken control of most of Panjshir Province, with resistance fighters retreating to the mountains.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Clashes in the valley ceased in mid-September.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] According to the Costs of War Project, 176,000 people were killed in the conflict, including 46,319 civilians, between 2001 and 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] According to the Uppsala Conflict Data Program, at least 212,191 people were killed in the conflict.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Though the state of war in the country ended in 2021, armed conflict persists in some regions amid fighting between the Taliban and the local branch of the Islamic State, as well as an anti-Taliban Republican insurgency.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is led by supreme leader Hibatullah Akhundzada and acting prime minister Hasan Akhund, who took office on 7 September 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Akhund is one of the four founders of the Taliban and was a deputy prime minister of the previous emirate; his appointment was seen as a compromise between moderates and hardliners.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] A new, all-male cabinet was formed, which included Abdul Hakim Haqqani as minister of justice.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] On 20 September 2021, United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres received a letter from acting minister of foreign affairs Amir Khan Muttaqi to formally claim Afghanistan's seat as a member state for their official spokesman in Doha, Suhail Shaheen.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The United Nations did not recognize the previous Taliban government and chose to work with the then government-in-exile instead.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Western nations suspended most of their humanitarian aid to Afghanistan following the Taliban's August 2021 takeover of the country; the World Bank and International Monetary Fund also halted their payments.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] More than half of Afghanistan's 39 million people faced an acute food shortage in October 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Human Rights Watch reported on 11 November 2021 that Afghanistan was facing widespread famine due to an economic and banking crisis.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban initially significantly tackled corruption, improving on the corruption perceptions index from 174th to 150th out of 180 countries from 2021 to 2022, but dropping to 162nd in 2023.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban have also reportedly reduced bribery and extortion in public service areas.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] At the same time, the human rights situation in the country has deteriorated.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Following the 2001 invasion, more than 5.7 million refugees returned to Afghanistan; however, in 2021, 2.6 million Afghans remained refugees, primarily in Iran and Pakistan, and another 4 million were internally displaced.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In October 2023, the Pakistani government ordered the expulsion of Afghans from Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Iran also decided to deport Afghan nationals back to Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Taliban authorities condemned the deportations of Afghans as an "inhuman act".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan faced a humanitarian crisis in late 2023.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] On 10 November 2024, Afghanistan's Foreign Ministry confirmed that Taliban representatives would attend the 2024 United Nations Climate Change Conference, marking the first time the country participated since the Taliban's return to power in 2021.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had been barred from previous summits due to the lack of global recognition of the Taliban regime.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In May 2025, Iran ordered the mass deportation of an estimated 4 million Afghan migrants and refugees.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The 2025–2026 hunger crisis in Afghanistan is one of the world's most severe, with over 17 million people—one-third of the population—requiring urgent food assistance.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Driven by persistent drought, economic collapse, and massive refugee returns, the crisis has left over 4.9 million children and women needing malnutrition treatment.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is located in Southern-Central Asia.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The region centered in Afghanistan is considered the "crossroads of Asia", and the country has had the nickname Heart of Asia.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] At over 652,864 km2 (252,072 sq mi), Afghanistan is the world's 41st largest country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] It is slightly bigger than France and smaller than Myanmar, and about the size of Texas in the United States.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] There is no coastline, as Afghanistan is landlocked.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The geography in Afghanistan is varied, but is mostly mountainous and rugged, with some unusual mountain ridges accompanied by plateaus and river basins.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] It is dominated by the Hindu Kush range, the western extension of the Himalayas that stretches to eastern Tibet via the Pamir Mountains and Karakoram Mountains in Afghanistan's far north-east.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Most of the highest points are in the east, consisting of fertile mountain valleys, often considered part of the "Roof of the World".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Hindu Kush ends at the west-central highlands, creating plains in the north and southwest, namely the Turkestan Plains and the Sistan Basin; these two regions consist of rolling grasslands and semi-deserts, as well as hot, windy deserts, respectively.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Forests exist in the corridor between the provinces of Nuristan and Paktika (see East Afghan montane conifer forests), and tundra in the northeast.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The country's highest point is Noshaq, at 7,492 m (24,580 ft) above sea level.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The lowest point is located in Jowzjan Province along the Amu River bank, at 258 m (846 ft) above sea level.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Despite having numerous rivers and reservoirs, large parts of the country are dry.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The endorheic Sistan Basin is one of the world's driest regions.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Amu Darya rises in the north of the Hindu Kush, while the nearby Hari River flows west towards Herat, and the Arghandab River flows from the central region southwards.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] To the south and west of the Hindu Kush flow a number of streams that are tributaries of the Indus River, such as the Helmand River.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Kabul River flows in an easterly direction to the Indus, ending at the Indian Ocean.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan receives heavy snow during the winter in the Hindu Kush and Pamir Mountains, and the melting snow in the spring season enters the rivers, lakes, and streams.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] However, two-thirds of the country's water flows into the neighboring countries of Iran, Pakistan, and Turkmenistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] As reported in 2010, the state needs more than US$2 billion to rehabilitate its irrigation systems so that the water is properly managed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In Afghanistan, forest cover accounts for approximately 2% of the total land area, equivalent to 1,208,440 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, which remained unchanged since 1990.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity), and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The northeastern Hindu Kush mountain range, located in and around the Badakhshan Province of Afghanistan, is situated in a geologically active area where earthquakes occur almost every year.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] They can be deadly and destructive, causing landslides in some parts or avalanches during the winter.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In June 2022, a destructive 5.9 earthquake struck near the border with Pakistan, killing at least 1,150 people and sparking fears of a major humanitarian crisis.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] On 7 October 2023, a 6.3 magnitude earthquake struck northwest of Herat, killing over 1,400 people.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The country is generally arid in the summers, with most rainfall falling between December and April.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The lower areas of northern and western Afghanistan are the driest, with precipitation more common in the east.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Although proximate to India, Afghanistan is mostly outside the monsoon zone, except the Nuristan Province, which occasionally receives summer monsoon rain.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Although Afghanistan has contributed minimally to global greenhouse gas emissions, it is one of the most vulnerable countries to climate change and least prepared to cope with its impacts.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Climate change in Afghanistan is causing more frequent and severe droughts.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Severe drought conditions affect 25 of the country's 34 provinces, impacting over half the population.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] These droughts cause desertification, reduce food and water security, disrupt agriculture, and cause internal displacement.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Extreme rainfall over short periods is also more likely, increasing the risk of floods and landslides.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Due to rising temperatures, almost 14% of Afghanistan's glacier coverage was lost between 1990 and 2015, increasing the risk of glacial lake outburst floods.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] By 2050, climate change could displace an additional 5 million people within Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Several types of mammals exist throughout Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Snow leopards and brown bears live in the high elevation alpine tundra regions.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Marco Polo sheep exclusively live in the Wakhan Corridor region of north-east Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Foxes, wolves, otters, deer, wild sheep, lynx and other big cats populate the mountain forest region of the east.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] In the semi-desert northern plains, wildlife include a variety of birds, hedgehogs, gophers, and large carnivores such as jackals and hyenas.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Gazelles, wild pigs and jackals populate the steppe plains of the south and west, while mongoose and cheetahs exist in the semi-desert south.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Marmots and ibex also live in the high mountains of Afghanistan, and pheasants exist in some parts of the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan hound is a native breed of dog known for its fast speed and its long hair; it is relatively known in the west.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Endemic fauna of Afghanistan includes the Afghan flying squirrel, Afghan snowfinch, *Paradactylodon* (or the "Paghman mountain salamander"), *Stigmella kasyi*, *Vulcaniella kabulensis*, Afghan leopard gecko, *Wheeleria parviflorellus*, among others.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan has a wide variety of birds despite its relatively arid climate – an estimated 460 species of which 235 breed within.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The forest region of Afghanistan has vegetation such as pine trees, spruce trees, fir trees and larches, whereas the steppe grassland regions consist of broadleaf trees, short grass, perennial plants and shrublands.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] The colder high elevation regions are composed of hardy grasses and small flowering plants.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Several regions are designated protected areas; there are three national parks: Band-e Amir, Wakhan and Nuristan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 8.85/10, ranking it 15th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Following the effective collapse of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan during the 2021 Taliban offensive, the Taliban declared the country an Islamic Emirate.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] A new caretaker government was announced on 7 September.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only the Russian Federation has recognized the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan as the *de jure* government of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In the V-Dem Democracy Indices, Afghanistan ranks amongst the lowest as a "closed autocracy," ranking at 176th and 177th out of 179 countries in electoral democracy and liberal democracy indices respectively.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan operates on a centralised unitary form of government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] A traditional instrument of governance in Afghanistan is the *loya jirga* (grand assembly), a Pashtun consultative meeting that was mainly organized for choosing a new head of state, adopting a new constitution, or to settle national or regional issue such as war.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Loya jirgas have been held since at least 1747, with the most recent one occurring from June to July 2022.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] President Ashraf Ghani, having fled the country during the Taliban advance to either Tajikistan or Uzbekistan, emerged in the United Arab Emirates and said that he supported such negotiations and was in talks to return to Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Many figures within the Taliban generally agreed that continuation of the 2004 Constitution of Afghanistan may, if correctly applied, be workable as the basis for the new religious state as their objections to the former government were political, and not religious.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Hours after the final flight of American troops left Kabul on 30 August, a Taliban official interviewed said that a new government would likely be announced as early as Friday 3 September after Jumu'ah.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] It was added that Hibatullah Akhundzada would be officially named Emir, with cabinet ministers being revealed at the Arg in an official ceremony.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Ghani Baradar would be named head of government as Prime Minister, while other important positions would go to Sirajuddin Haqqani and Mullah Yaqoob.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Beneath the supreme leader, day-to-day governance will be entrusted to the cabinet.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In a report by CNN-News18, sources said the new government was going to be governed similarly to Iran with Hibatullah Akhundzada as supreme leader similar to the role of Saayid Ali Khamenei, and would be based out of Kandahar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Baradar or Yaqoob would be head of government as Prime minister.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The government's ministries and agencies will be under a cabinet presided over by the Prime Minister.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The Supreme Leader would preside over an executive body known as the Supreme Council with anywhere from 11 to 72 members.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Hakim Haqqani is likely to be promoted to Chief justice.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] According to the report, the new government will take place within the framework of an amended 1964 Constitution of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Government formation was delayed due to concerns about forming a broad-based government acceptable to the international community.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] It was later added however that the Taliban's Rahbari Shura, the group's leadership council was divided between the hardline Haqqani Network and moderate Abdul Ghani Baradar over appointments needed to form an "inclusive" government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Reports claimed that this culminated in a skirmish which led to Baradar being injured and treated in Pakistan, however this was denied by Baradar himself.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As of early September 2021 the Taliban were planning the cabinet to be men-only.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Journalists and other human rights activists, mostly women, protested in Herat and Kabul, calling for women to be included.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The acting Cabinet announced on 7 September was men-only, and the Ministry of Women's Affairs was abolished.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only Russia has recognized the Taliban government as the legitimate authorities of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The U.N has stated that recognition was impossible so long as restrictions on female education and employment remained.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] On 16 September 2024, the Taliban suspended polio vaccination campaigns in Afghanistan, as reported by the United Nations, posing a significant risk to global polio eradication efforts.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In a decree by Hibatullah Akhundzada on 15 August 2025, the description of the government as interim was dropped, with all ministers remaining in their posts, but on a permanent rather than acting basis.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is administratively divided into 34 provinces (*wilayat*).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Each province has a governor and a capital.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country is further divided into nearly 400 provincial districts, each of which normally covers a city or several villages.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Each district is represented by a district governor.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are now appointed by the Prime Minister of Afghanistan, and the district governors are selected by the provincial governors.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are representatives of the central government in Kabul and are responsible for all administrative and formal issues within their provinces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] There are also provincial councils that are elected through direct and general elections for four years.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The functions of provincial councils are to take part in provincial development planning and to participate in the monitoring and appraisal of other provincial governance institutions.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] According to article 140 of the constitution and the presidential decree on electoral law, mayors of cities should be elected through free and direct elections for a four-year term.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In practice however, mayors are appointed by the government.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan became a member of the United Nations in 1946.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Relations with Pakistan have often been tense for various reasons such as the Durand Line border issue and alleged Pakistani involvement in Afghan insurgent groups.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The present Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan is currently partially recognized, but has had notable unofficial ties with China, Pakistan, and Qatar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Under the previous Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, it enjoyed cordial relations with a number of NATO and allied nations, particularly the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, and Turkey.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2012, the United States and the then-republic in Afghanistan signed their Strategic Partnership Agreement in which Afghanistan became a major non-NATO ally.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Such qualification was rescinded by US President Joe Biden in July 2022.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The Armed Forces of the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan captured a large amount of weapons, hardware, vehicles, aerocrafts, and equipment from the Afghan National Security Forces following the 2021 Taliban offensive and the Fall of Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The total value of the captured equipment has been estimated at US$83 billion.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Homosexuality is taboo in Afghan society; according to the Penal Code, homosexual intimacy is punished by up to a year in prison.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Under Sharia law offenders can be punished by death.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] However, an ancient tradition involving male homosexual acts between children and older men (typically wealthy warlords or elite people) called *bacha bazi* persists albeit punishable by the death penalty under Taliban law.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Religious minorities such as Sikhs, Hindus, and Christians have reportedly faced persecution.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Since May 2022, all women in Afghanistan have been required by law to wear full-body coverings when in public (either a burqa or an abaya paired with a niqāb, which leaves only the eyes uncovered).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] First Deputy Leader Sirajuddin Haqqani claimed the decree is only advisory and no form of hijab is compulsory in Afghanistan, though this contradicts the reality.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] It has been speculated that there is a genuine internal policy division over women's rights between hardliners, including leader Hibatullah Akhundzada, and pragmatists, though they publicly present a united front.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Another decree was issued shortly after the first, requiring female TV presenters to cover their faces during broadcasts.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban takeover, suicides among women have become more common, and the country could now be one of the few where the rate of suicide among women surpasses that among men.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In May 2022, the Taliban dissolved Afghanistan's Human Rights Commission along with four other government departments, citing the country's budget deficit.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] ICC member states are obliged to arrest wanted persons if they are on their territory.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's nominal GDP was $20.1 billion in 2020, or $81 billion by purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Its GDP per capita is $2,459 (PPP) and $611 by nominal.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Despite having $1 trillion or more in mineral deposits, it remains one of the world's least developed countries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Its economic output per capita is among the lowest of any country as of 2026.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's rough physical geography and its landlocked status has been cited as reasons why the country has always been among the least developed in the modern era – a factor where progress is also slowed by contemporary conflict and political instability.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country imports over $7 billion worth of goods but exports only $784 million, mainly fruits and nuts.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The service sector contributed the most to the GDP (55.9%) followed by agriculture (23%) and industry (21.1%).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Da Afghanistan Bank serves as the central bank of the nation and the Afghani (AFN) is the national currency, with an exchange rate of about 75 Afghanis to 1 US dollar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] A number of local and foreign banks operate in the country, including the Afghanistan International Bank, New Kabul Bank, Azizi Bank, Pashtany Bank, Standard Chartered Bank, and the First Micro Finance Bank.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, one of the main drivers for the economic recovery was the return of over 5 million expatriates, who brought with them entrepreneurship and wealth-creating skills as well as much needed funds to start up businesses.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Many Afghans got involved in construction, which was one of the largest industries in the country at the time.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Some of the major national construction projects include the $35 billion New Kabul City next to the capital, the Aino Mena project in Kandahar, and the Ghazi Amanullah Khan Town near Jalalabad.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Similar development projects have also begun in Herat, Mazar-e-Sharif, and other cities.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] An estimated 400,000 people enter the labor market each year.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Several small companies and factories began operating in different parts of the country, which not only provide revenues to the government but also create new jobs.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Improvements to the business environment have resulted in more than $1.5 billion in telecom investment and created more than 100,000 jobs since 2003.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghan rugs are becoming popular again, allowing many carpet dealers around the country to hire more workers; in 2016–17 it was the fourth most exported group of items.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is a member of WTO, SAARC, ECO, and OIC.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2018, a majority of imports come from either Iran, China, Pakistan and Kazakhstan, while 84% of exports are to Pakistan and India.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban's takeover of the country in August 2021, the United States has frozen about $9 billion in assets belonging to the Afghan central bank, blocking the Taliban from accessing billions of dollars held in US bank accounts.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The GDP of Afghanistan is estimated to have dropped by 20% following the Taliban return to power.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Following this, after months of free-fall, the Afghan economy began stabilizing, as a result of the Taliban's restrictions on smuggled imports, limits on banking transactions, and UN aid.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2023, the Afghan economy began seeing signs of revival.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] This has also been followed by stable exchange rates, low inflation, stable revenue collection, and the rise of trade in exports.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In the third quarter of 2023, the Afghani rose to be the best performing currency in the world, climbing over 9% against the US dollar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Agricultural production is the backbone of Afghanistan's economy and has traditionally dominated the economy, employing about 40% of the workforce as of 2018.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country is known for producing pomegranates, grapes, apricots, melons, and several other fresh and dry fruits.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan also became the world's top producer of cannabis in 2010.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In March 2023, however, cannabis production was banned by a decree from Hibatullah Akhundzada.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Saffron, the most expensive spice, grows in Afghanistan, particularly Herat Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In recent years, there has been an uptick in saffron production, which authorities and farmers are using to try to replace poppy cultivation.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Between 2012 and 2019, the saffron cultivated and produced in Afghanistan was consecutively ranked the world's best by the International Taste and Quality Institute.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Production hit record high in 2019 (19,469 kg of saffron), and one kilogram is sold domestically between $634 and $1147.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The availability of cheap diesel-powered water pumps imported from China and Pakistan, and in the 2010s, of cheap solar power to pump water, resulted in expansion of agriculture and population in the southwestern deserts of Afghanistan in Kandahar, Helmand and Nimruz provinces in the 2010s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Wells have gradually been deepened, but water resources are limited.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Opium is the major crop, but as of 2022, was under attack by the new Taliban government which, to suppress opium production, was systematically suppressing water pumping.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In a 2023 report, poppy cultivation in southern Afghanistan was reduced by over 80% as a result of Taliban campaigns to stop its use toward opium.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] This included a 99% reduction of opium growth in the Helmand Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In November 2023, a U.N report showed that in the entirety of Afghanistan, poppy cultivation dropped by over 95%, removing it from its place as being the world's largest opium producer.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country's natural resources include: coal, copper, iron ore, lithium, uranium, rare earth elements, chromite, gold, zinc, talc, barite, sulfur, lead, marble, precious and semi-precious stones, natural gas, and petroleum.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, US and Afghan government officials estimated that untapped mineral deposits located in 2007 by the US Geological Survey are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution estimated that if Afghanistan generates about $10 billion per year from its mineral deposits, its gross national product would double and provide long-term funding for critical needs.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The United States Geological Survey (USGS) estimated in 2006 that northern Afghanistan has an average 460 million m3 (2.9 billion bbl) of crude oil, 440 billion m3 (15.7 trillion cu ft) of natural gas, and 67 billion L (562 million US bbl) of natural gas liquids.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2011, Afghanistan signed an oil exploration contract with China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) for the development of three oil fields along the Amu Darya river in the north.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country has significant amounts of lithium, copper, gold, coal, iron ore, and other minerals.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The Khanashin carbonatite in Helmand Province contains 1,000,000 tonnes (980,000 long tons; 1,100,000 short tons) of rare earth elements.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2007, a 30-year lease was granted for the Aynak copper mine to the China Metallurgical Group for $3 billion, making it the biggest foreign investment and private business venture in Afghanistan's history.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The state-run Steel Authority of India won the mining rights to develop the huge Hajigak iron ore deposit in central Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Government officials estimate that 30% of the country's untapped mineral deposits are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] One official asserted that "this will become the backbone of the Afghan economy" and a Pentagon memo stated that Afghanistan could become the "Saudi Arabia of lithium".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The lithium reserves of 21 Mio. tons could amount to the ones of Bolivia, which is currently viewed as the country with the largest lithium reserves.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Other larger deposits are the ones of bauxite and cobalt.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Access to biocapacity in Afghanistan is lower than world average.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2016, Afghanistan had 0.43 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, much less than the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2016 Afghanistan used 0.73 global hectares of biocapacity per person—their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] This means they use just under double as much biocapacity as Afghanistan contains.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As a result, Afghanistan is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In September 2023, the Taliban signed mining contracts worth $6.5 billion, with extractions based on gold, iron, lead, and zinc in the provinces of Herat, Ghor, Logar, and Takhar.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] According to the World Bank, 98% of the rural population have access to electricity in 2018, up from 28% in 2008.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As of 2016, Afghanistan produces 1,400 megawatts of power, but still imports the majority of electricity via transmission lines from Iran and the Central Asian states.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The majority of electricity production is via hydropower, helped by the amount of rivers and streams that flow from the mountains.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] However electricity is not always reliable and blackouts happen, including in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In recent years an increasing number of solar, biomass and wind power plants have been constructed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Currently under development are the CASA-1000 project which will transmit electricity from Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, and the Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India (TAPI) gas pipeline.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Power is managed by the Da Afghanistan Breshna Sherkat (DABS, Afghanistan Electricity Company).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Important dams include the Kajaki Dam, Dahla Dam, and the Sardeh Band Dam.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Tourism is a small industry in Afghanistan due to security issues.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Nevertheless, some 20,000 foreign tourists visit the country annually as of 2016.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In particular an important region for domestic and international tourism is the picturesque Bamyan Valley, which includes lakes, canyons and historical sites, helped by the fact it is in a safe area away from insurgent activity.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Smaller numbers visit and trek in regions such as the Wakhan Valley, which is also one of the world's most remote communities.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] From the late 1960s onwards, Afghanistan was a popular stop on the famous hippie trail, attracting many Europeans and Americans.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Coming from Iran, the trail traveled through various Afghan provinces and cities including Herat, Kandahar and Kabul before crossing to northern Pakistan, northern India, and Nepal.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Tourism peaked in 1977, the year before the start of political instability and armed conflict.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The city of Ghazni has significant history and historical sites, and together with Bamyan city have in recent years been voted Islamic Cultural Capital and South Asia Cultural Capital respectively.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The cities of Herat, Kandahar, Balkh, and Zaranj are also very historic.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The Minaret of Jam in the Hari River valley is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] A cloak reputedly worn by Islam's prophet Muhammad is kept in the Shrine of the Cloak in Kandahar, a city founded by Alexander the Great and the first capital of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The citadel of Alexander in the western city of Herat has been renovated in recent years and is a popular attraction.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In the north of the country is the Shrine of Ali, believed by many to be the location where Ali was buried.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The National Museum of Afghanistan in Kabul hosts a large number of Buddhist, Bactrian Greek and early Islamic antiquities; the museum suffered greatly by civil war but has been slowly restoring since the early 2000s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Unexpectedly, tourism has seen improvement in Afghanistan following the Taliban takeover.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Active efforts by the Taliban encouraged tourism to increase from 691 tourists in 2021, to 2,300 in 2022, to 5,200 in 2023, with some estimates of between 7,000 and 10,000.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] This is, however, threatened by the Islamic State – Khorasan Province, who took responsibility for attacks on tourists, such as the 2024 Bamyan shooting.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Telecommunication services in Afghanistan are provided by Afghan Telecom, Afghan Wireless, Etisalat, MTN Group, and Roshan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country uses its own space satellite called Afghansat 1, which provides services to millions of phone, internet, and television subscribers.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] By 2001 following years of civil war, telecommunications was virtually a non-existent sector, but by 2016 it had grown to a $2 billion industry, with 22 million mobile phone subscribers and 5 million internet users.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The sector employs at least 120,000 people nationwide.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Due to Afghanistan's geography, transport between various parts of the country has historically been difficult.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The Ring Road is crucially important for domestic and international trade and the economy.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] A key portion of the Ring Road is the Salang Tunnel, completed in 1964, which facilitates travel through the Hindu Kush mountain range and connects northern and southern Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] It is the only land route that connects Central Asia to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Several mountain passes allow travel between the Hindu Kush in other areas.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Serious traffic accidents are common on Afghan roads and highways, particularly on the Kabul–Kandahar and the Kabul–Jalalabad Road.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Traveling by bus in Afghanistan remains dangerous due to militant activities.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Air transport in Afghanistan is provided by the national carrier, Ariana Afghan Airlines, and by the private company Kam Air.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Airlines from a number of countries also provide flights in and out of the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] These include Air India, Emirates, Gulf Air, Iran Aseman Airlines, Pakistan International Airlines, and Turkish Airlines.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country has four international airports: Kabul International Airport (formerly Hamid Karzai International Airport), Kandahar International Airport, Herat International Airport, and Mazar-e Sharif International Airport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Including domestic airports, there are 43.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Bagram Air Base is a major military airfield.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] These lines are used for freight only and there is no passenger service.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] A rail line between Khaf, Iran and Herat, western Afghanistan, intended for both freight and passengers, was under construction as of 2019.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] About 125 kilometres (78 mi) of the line will lie on the Afghan side.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Private vehicle ownership has increased substantially since the early 2000s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Taxis are yellow and consist of both cars and auto rickshaws.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In rural Afghanistan, villagers often use donkeys, mules or horses to transport or carry goods.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Camels are primarily used by the Kochi nomads.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Bicycles are popular throughout Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan was estimated at 35.7 million as of 2024 by the Afghanistan National Statistics and Information Authority, whereas the UN estimates over 42.0 million.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 1979 the total population was reported to be about 15.5 million.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] About 25.3% are urbanite, 70.4% live in rural areas, and the remaining 4.3% are nomadic.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] An additional 3 million or so Afghans are temporarily housed in neighboring Pakistan and Iran, most of whom were born and raised in those two countries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As of 2013, Afghanistan was the largest refugee-producing country in the world, a title held for 32 years.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The current population growth rate is 2.37%, one of the highest in the world outside of Africa.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] This population is expected to reach 82 million by 2050 if current population trends continue.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan increased steadily until the 1980s, when civil war caused millions to flee to other countries such as Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Millions have since returned and the war conditions contribute to the country having the highest fertility rate outside Africa.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's healthcare has recovered since the turn of the century, causing falls in infant mortality and increases in life expectancy, although it has the lowest life expectance of any country outside Africa.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] This (along with other factors such as returning refugees) caused rapid population growth in the 2000s that has only recently started to slow down.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan 2024 total fertility rate has been estimated at 4.4.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In 2022 it was 4.5, about twice the world average rate.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The rate has fallen since the early 1980s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As estimated by the CIA World Factbook, 26% of the population was urbanized as of 2020.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] This is one of the lowest figures in the world; in Asia it is only higher than Cambodia, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization has increased rapidly, particularly in the capital Kabul, due to returning refugees from Pakistan and Iran after 2001, internally displaced people, and rural migrants.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization in Afghanistan is different from typical urbanization in that it is centered on just a few cities.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Kabul is the largest city, with a population of 5 million.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The other large cities are located generally in the "ring" around the Central Highlands, namely Kandahar in the south, Herat in the west, Mazar-i-Sharif, Kunduz in the north, and Jalalabad in the east.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghans are divided into several ethnolinguistic groups.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] According to research data by several institutions in 2019, the Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group, comprising 42%, followed by Tajiks, comprising 27% of the country's population.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The other two major ethnic groups are the Hazaras and Uzbeks, each at 9%.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] A further 10 other ethnic groups are recognized and each are represented in the Afghan National Anthem.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Dari and Pashto are the official languages of Afghanistan; bilingualism is very common.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Dari, which is also referred to as Eastern Persian as it is a variety of and mutually intelligible with Persian (and very often called 'Farsi' by some Afghans like in Iran), functions as the lingua franca in Kabul as well as in much of the northern and northwestern parts of the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Native speakers of Dari, of any ethnicity, are sometimes called Farsiwans.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Pashto is the native tongue of the Pashtuns, although many of them are also fluent in Dari while some non-Pashtuns are fluent in Pashto.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Despite the Pashtuns having been dominant in Afghan politics for centuries, Dari remained the preferred language for government and bureaucracy.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] According to CIA World Factbook, Dari Persian is spoken by 78% (L1 + L2) and functions as the lingua franca, while Pashto is spoken by 50%, Uzbek 10%, English 5%, Turkmen 2%, Urdu 2%, Pashayi 1%, Nuristani 1%, Arabic 1%, and Balochi 1% (2021 est).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Data represent the most widely spoken languages; shares sum to more than 100% because there is much bilingualism in the country and because respondents were allowed to select more than one language.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] There are a number of smaller regional languages, including Uzbek, Turkmen, Balochi, Pashayi, and Nuristani.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] When it comes to foreign languages among the populace, many are able to speak or understand Hindustani (Urdu-Hindi), partly due to returning Afghan refugees from Pakistan and the popularity of Bollywood films respectively.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] English is also understood by some of the population, and has been gaining popularity as of the 2000s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Some Afghans retain some ability in Russian, which was taught in public schools during the 1980s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The CIA estimated in 2009 that 99.7% of the Afghan population was Muslim and most are thought to adhere to the Sunni Hanafi school.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] According to Pew Research Center, as much as 90% are of the Sunni denomination, 7% Shia and 3% non-denominational.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Conversion away from Islam is persecuted, limiting religious freedom.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Sikhs and Hindus are also found in certain major cities (namely Kabul, Jalalabad, Ghazni, Kandahar) accompanied by gurdwaras and mandirs.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] According to Deutsche Welle in September 2021, 250 remain in the country after 67 were evacuated to India.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] There was a small Jewish community in Afghanistan, living mainly in Herat and Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Over the years, this small community was forced to leave due to decades of warfare and religious persecution.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] By the end of the twentieth century, nearly the entire community had emigrated to Israel and the United States, with one known exception, Herat-born Zablon Simintov.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] He remained for years, being the caretaker of the only remaining Afghan synagogue.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] He left the country for the US after the second Taliban takeover.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] A woman who left shortly after him has since been identified as the likely last Jew in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Christians, who number 500–8,000, practice their faith secretly due to intense societal opposition, and there are no public churches.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Education in Afghanistan is overseen by the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Higher Education.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] There are over 16,000 schools in the country and roughly 9 million students.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Of this, about 60% are males and 40% females.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] However, the new regime has thus far forbidden female teachers and female students from returning to secondary schools.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Over 174,000 students are enrolled in different universities around the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Former Education Minister Ghulam Farooq Wardak had stated that construction of 8,000 schools is required for the remaining children who are deprived of formal learning.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As of 2018 the literacy rate of the population age 15 and older is 43.02% (males 55.48% and females 29.81%).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The top universities in Afghanistan are the American University of Afghanistan (AUAF) followed by Kabul University (KU), both of which are located in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The National Military Academy of Afghanistan, modeled after the United States Military Academy at West Point, was a four-year military development institution dedicated to graduating officers for the Afghan Armed Forces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The Afghan Defense University was constructed near Qargha in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Major universities outside of Kabul include Kandahar University in the south, Herat University in the northwest, Balkh University and Kunduz University in the north, Nangarhar University and Khost University in the east.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] After the Taliban regained power in 2021, it became unclear to what extent female education would continue in the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In March 2022, after they had been closed for some time, it was announced that secondary education would be reopened shortly.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] However, shortly before reopening, the order was rescinded and schools for older girls remained closed.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Despite the ban, six provinces, Balkh, Kunduz, Jowzjan, Sar-I-Pul, Faryab, and the Day Kundi, still allow girls' schools from grade 6 and up.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In December 2023, investigations were being held by the United Nations on the claim that Afghan girls of all ages were allowed to study at religious schools.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] As of November 2024, some parts of the country allow women to attend religious schools to pursue dentistry, nursing, and other subjects.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] According to the Human Development Index, Afghanistan is the 15th least developed country in the world.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The average life expectancy is estimated to be around 60 years.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country's maternal mortality rate is 396 deaths/100,000 live births and its infant mortality rate is 66 to 112.8 deaths in every 1,000 live births.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The Ministry of Public Health plans to cut the infant mortality rate to 400 for every 100,000 live births before 2020.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The country has more than 3,000 midwives, with an additional 300 to 400 being trained each year.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] There are over 100 hospitals in Afghanistan, with the most advanced treatments being available in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The French Medical Institute for Children and Indira Gandhi Children's Hospital in Kabul are the leading children's hospitals in the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Some of the other leading hospitals in Kabul include the Jamhuriat Hospital and Jinnah Hospital.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] In spite of all this, many Afghans travel to Pakistan and India for advanced treatment.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] It was reported in 2006 that nearly 60% of the Afghan population lives within a two-hour walk of the nearest health facility.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] The disability rate is also high in Afghanistan due to the decades of war.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] It was reported recently that about 80,000 people are missing limbs.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p02] Non-governmental charities such as Save the Children and Mahboba's Promise assist orphans in association with governmental structures.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have both common cultural features and those that differ between the regions of Afghanistan, each with distinctive cultures partly as a result of geographic obstacles that divide the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Family is the mainstay of Afghan society and families are often headed by a patriarch.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] In the southern and eastern region, the people live according to the Pashtun culture by following Pashtunwali (the Pashtun way).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Key tenets of Pashtunwali include hospitality, the provision of sanctuary to those seeking refuge, and revenge for the shedding of blood.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Pashtuns are largely connected to the culture of Central Asia and the Iranian Plateau.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The remaining Afghans are culturally Persian and Turkic.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Some non-Pashtuns who live in proximity with Pashtuns have adopted Pashtunwali in a process called Pashtunization, while some Pashtuns have been Persianized.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Those who have lived in Pakistan and Iran over the last 30 years have been further influenced by the cultures of those neighboring nations.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan people are known to be strongly religious.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghans, particularly Pashtuns, are noted for their tribal solidarity and high regard for personal honor.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] There are various Afghan tribes, and an estimated 2–3 million nomads.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghan culture is deeply Islamic, but pre-Islamic practices persist.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Child marriage is prevalent; in 2017, Human Rights Watch described the legal age for marriage of girls as being 16, or 15 with the consent of the father or a judge.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The most preferred marriage in Afghan society is to one's parallel cousin, and the groom is often expected to pay a bride price.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] In the villages, families typically occupy mudbrick houses, or compounds with mudbrick or stone walled houses.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Villages typically have a headman (*malik*), a master for water distribution (*mirab*) and a religious teacher (*mullah*).
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Men would typically work on the fields, joined by women during harvest.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] About 15% of the population are nomadic, locally called *kochis*.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] When nomads pass villages they often buy supplies such as tea, wheat and kerosene from the villagers; villagers buy wool and milk from the nomads.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghan clothing for both men and women typically consists of various forms of shalwar kameez, especially *perahan tunban* and *khet partug*.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Women would normally wear a *chador* for head covering; some women, typically from highly conservative communities, wear the *burqa*, a full body covering.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] These were worn by some women of the Pashtun community well before Islam came to the region, but the Taliban enforced this dress on women when they were in power.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Another popular dress is the *chapan* which acts as a coat.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The *karakul* is a hat made from the fur of a specific regional breed of sheep.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] It was favored by former kings of Afghanistan and became known to much of the world in the 21st century when it was constantly worn by President Hamid Karzai.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The *pakol* is another traditional hat originating from the far east of the country; it was popularly worn by the guerrilla leader Ahmad Shah Massoud.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The *Mazari hat* originates from northern Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The nation has a complex history that has survived either in its current cultures or in the form of various languages and monuments.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan contains many remnants from all ages, including Greek and Buddhist stupas, monasteries, monuments, temples, and Islamic minarets.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Among the most well known are the Great Mosque of Herat, the Blue Mosque, the Minaret of Jam, the Chil Zena, the Qala-i Bost in Lashkargah, the ancient Greek city of Ai-Khanoum.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] However, many of its historic monuments have been damaged in modern times due to the civil wars.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The two famous Buddhas of Bamiyan were destroyed by the Taliban, who regarded them as idolatrous.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] As there was no colonialism in the modern era in Afghanistan, European-style architecture is rare but does exist: the Victory Arch at Paghman and the Darul Aman Palace in Kabul were built in this style in the 1920s.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghan architecture also ranges deep into India such as the city of Agra, and the tomb of Sher Shah Suri, an Afghan Emperor of India.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Carpet weaving is an ancient practice in Afghanistan, and many of these are still handmade by tribal and nomadic people today.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Carpets have been produced in the region for thousands of years and traditionally done by women.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Some crafters express their feelings through the designs of rugs; for example after the outbreak of the Soviet–Afghan War, "war rugs", a variant of Afghan rugs, were created with designs representing pain and misery caused by the conflict.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Every province has its own specific characteristics in making rugs.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] In some of the Turkic-populated areas in the north-west, bride and wedding ceremony prices are driven by the bride's weaving skills.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Pottery has been crafted in Afghanistan for millennia.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The village of Istalif, north of Kabul, is in particular a major center, known for its unique turquoise and green pottery, and their methods of crafting have remained the same for centuries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Much of *lapis lazuli* stones were earthed in modern-day Afghanistan which were used in Chinese porcelain as cobalt blue, later used in ancient Mesopotamia and Turkey.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The lands of Afghanistan have a long history of art, with the world's earliest known usage of oil painting found in cave murals in the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] A notable art style that developed in Afghanistan and eastern Pakistan is Gandhara Art, produced by a fusion of Greco-Roman art and Buddhist art between the 1st and 7th centuries CE.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Later eras saw increased use of the Persian miniature style, with Kamaleddin Behzad of Herat being one of the most notable miniature artists of the Timurid and early Safavid periods.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Since the 1900s, the nation began to use Western techniques in art.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Abdul Ghafoor Breshna was a prominent Afghan painter and sketch artist from Kabul during the 20th century.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Classic Persian and Pashto poetry are a cherished part of Afghan culture.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Poetry has always been one of the major educational pillars in the region, to the level that it has integrated itself into culture.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] One of the poetic styles is called landay.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] A popular theme in Afghan folklore and mythology are Divs, monstrous creatures.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Thursdays are traditionally "poetry night" in the city of Herat when men, women and children gather and recite both ancient and modern poems.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Pashto literature, although quantitatively remarkable and in great growth in the last century, has always had an essentially local meaning and importance, feeling the influence of both Persian literature and the contiguous literatures of India.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Both main literatures, from the second half of the nineteenth century, have shown themselves to be sensitive to genres, movements and stylistic features imported from Europe.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Khushal Khan Khattak of the 17th century is considered the national poet.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Other notable poets include Rabi'a Balkhi, Jami, Rahman Baba, Khalilullah Khalili, and Parween Pazhwak.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghan classical music has close historical links with Indian classical music and use the same Hindustani terminology and theories like raga.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Genres of this style of music include ghazal (poetic music) and instruments such as the Indian tabla, sitar and harmonium, and local instruments like zerbaghali, as well as dayereh and tanbur which are also known in Central Asia, the Caucasus and the Middle East.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The rubab is the country's national instrument and precurses the Indian sarod instrument.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Some of the famous artists of classical music include Ustad Sarahang and Sarban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Pop music developed in the 1950s through Radio Kabul and was influential in social change.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] During this time female artists also started appearing, at first Mermon Parwin.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Perhaps the most famous artist of this genre was Ahmad Zahir, who synthesized many genres and continues to be renowned for his voice and rich lyrics long after his death in 1979.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Other notable masters of traditional or popular Afghan music include Nashenas, Ubaidullah Jan, Mahwash, Ahmad Wali, Farhad Darya, and Naghma.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Attan is the national dance of Afghanistan, a group dance popularly performed by Afghans of all backgrounds.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The dance is considered part of Afghan identity.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan has around 350 radio stations and over 200 television stations.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Radio Television Afghanistan, originating from 1925, is the state public broadcaster.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Television programs began airing in the 1970s and today there are many private television channels such as TOLO and Shamshad TV.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The first Afghan newspaper was published in 1873, and there are hundreds of print outlets today.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] By the 1920s, Radio Kabul was broadcasting local radio services.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Voice of America, BBC, and Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty (RFE/RL) broadcast in both of Afghanistan's official languages on radio.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Press restrictions have been gradually relaxed and private media diversified since 2002, after more than two decades of tight controls.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have long been accustomed to watching Indian Bollywood films and listening to its filmi songs.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] It has been claimed that Afghanistan is among the biggest markets for the Hindi film industry.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The stereotypes of Afghans in India (*Kabuliwala* or *Pathani*) have also been represented in some Bollywood films by actors.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Many Bollywood film stars have roots in Afghanistan, including Salman Khan, Saif Ali Khan, Aamir Khan, Feroz Khan, Kader Khan, Naseeruddin Shah, Zarine Khan, Celina Jaitly, and a number of others.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Several Bollywood films have been shot inside Afghanistan, including *Dharmatma*, *Khuda Gawah*, *Escape from Taliban*, and *Kabul Express*.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghan cuisine is largely based upon the nation's chief crops, such as wheat, maize, barley and rice.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Accompanying these staples are native fruits and vegetables as well as dairy products such as milk, yogurt, and whey.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Kabuli palaw is the national dish of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The nation's culinary specialties reflect its ethnic and geographic diversity.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan is known for its high-quality pomegranates, grapes, and sweet melons.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] A typical Afghan diet consists of naan, yogurt, rice, and meat.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan's official New Year starts with Nowruz (natively known as "*Nawroz*"), an ancient tradition that started as a Zoroastrian celebration in present-day Iran, and with which it shares the annual celebration along with several other countries.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] It occurs every year at the vernal equinox.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] In Afghanistan, Nowruz is typically celebrated with music and dance, as well as holding buzkashi tournaments.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Yaldā, another nationally celebrated ancient tradition, commemorates the ancient goddess Mithra and marks the longest night of the year on the eve of the winter solstice (*Čilli-yi Zimistān*; usually falling on 20 or 21 December), during which families gather together to recite poetry and eat fruit.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] As a predominantly Muslim country, Islamic events and festivals such as Ramadan, Eid al-Fitr and Ashura are widely celebrated annually in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Sikh festival of Vaisakhi is celebrated by the Sikh community and the Hindu festival Diwali by the Hindu community.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] National Independence Day is celebrated on 19 August to mark the Anglo-Afghan Treaty of 1919 and the country's full independence.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Several international celebrations are also officially held in Afghanistan, such as International Workers' Day, and International Women's Day.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Some regional festivals include the Red Flower Festival (during Nowruz) in Mazar-i-Sharif, and the Damboora Festival in Bamyan Province.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Sport in Afghanistan is managed by the Afghan Sports Federation.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Cricket and association football are the two most popular sports in the country.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Sports Federation promotes cricket, association football, basketball, volleyball, golf, handball, boxing, taekwondo, weightlifting, bodybuilding, track and field, skating, bowling, snooker, chess, and other sports.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national basketball team won the first team sports title at the 2010 South Asian Games.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] In 2012, the country's 3x3 basketball team won the gold medal at the 2012 Asian Beach Games.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] In 2013, Afghanistan's football team followed as it won the SAFF Championship.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan national cricket team, which was formed in 2001, won the 2009–10 ICC Intercontinental Cup.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The team played in the 2015, 2019, and 2023 Cricket World Cups.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) is the official governing body of the sport and is based in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Alokozay Kabul International Cricket Ground serves as the nation's main cricket stadium.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] There are several other stadiums throughout the country, including the Ghazi Amanullah Khan International Cricket Stadium near Jalalabad.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] Domestically, cricket is played between teams from different provinces.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national football team has been competing in international football since 1941.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The national team plays its home games at the Ghazi Stadium in Kabul, while football in Afghanistan is governed by the Afghanistan Football Federation.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The national team has never competed or qualified for the FIFA World Cup but won an international football trophy in 2013.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The country also has a national team in the sport of futsal, a 5-a-side variation of football.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The traditional and the national sport of Afghanistan is buzkashi, particularly popular in the north.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] It is similar to polo, played by horsemen in two teams, each trying to grab and hold a goat carcass.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Hound (a type of running dog) originated in Afghanistan and was used in wolf hunting.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] The **Afghanistan women's national cricket team** was the team that represented the country of Afghanistan in international women's cricket matches.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] The team was first established in 2010, but played only a single tournament amidst opposition from Islamists opposed to women's sport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] An attempt at revival was made in 2020 when the Afghanistan Cricket Board awarded central contracts to 25 players.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] However, the team was disbanded following the 2021 Taliban offensive and capture of Kabul in accordance with the Taliban's ban on women's sport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] The team was first formed in 2010, but disbanded in 2014.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] Although the team never played representative cricket in ICC competition, it had been scheduled to take part in the 2011 ACC Women's Twenty20 Championship in Kuwait, which ran from 17 to 25 February.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] The team was forced to withdraw from the tournament before travelling to Kuwait due to elements in Afghanistan opposing women's participation in sport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] In 2012, the team participated in a 6 team tournament in Dushanbe, Tajikistan, and became Champion by winning four matches and tying one.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] In November 2020, the Afghanistan Cricket Board awarded central contracts to twenty-five players, in their bid to form a national team to take part in ICC tournaments.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] In October 2020, ACB organised skills and fitness camp as well as the national team trial camp at the Alokozay Kabul International Cricket Ground for the players who were selected from the talent pool.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] In April 2021, the ICC awarded permanent Test and One Day International (ODI) status to all full member women's teams.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] Concerns regarding the safety of the Afghan women cricketers and development of women's cricket in Afghanistan were raised following the 2021 Taliban offensive and the 15 August 2021 Fall of Kabul.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] As of 31 August 2021, three of the Afghan women's cricket team, Roya Samim and her two sisters, were in exile in Canada.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] Samim said that the team members remaining in Afghanistan were afraid of the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] She stated that the International Cricket Council (ICC) had failed to respond to emails calling for help from team members seeking evacuation from Afghanistan, and that the Afghan Cricket Board (ACB) had given no help except to say "Wait".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] The ICC said that it was not aware of having received emails asking for help and that it was closely monitoring the situation.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] According to *The Guardian*, the ICC was keeping in contact with the ACB in order to avoid acting unilaterally.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] An ACB spokesperson stated that the Taliban appeared to support the continuation of men's cricket.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] One of the team members was threatened by the Taliban after the fall of Kabul with being killed "if [she tried] to play cricket again".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] Another team member, in exile as of 2 September 2021, stated that the ICC "never help" the women's cricket team, "always disappoint" the team and only communicate with the ACB rather than contacting the women's team directly.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] Several of the team members expressed their expectations and hopes for the women's team to reorganise.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] Hamid Shinwari, chief executive officer of the ACB, stated in early September 2021 that he expected the Afghan women's cricket team "to be stopped".
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] The Taliban also said that Afghan women would be barred from playing sport.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] However, Afghanistan Cricket Board's chairman Azizullah Fazli clarified later in an Al Jazeera interview that women will be allowed to play cricket and that they would not be stopped.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] As of April 2023, most of the squad had re-united in Australia.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] There have been multiple attempts to form a refugee Afghan women's team.
[src:afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team/afghanistan-women-s-national-cricket-team] In January 2025, 21 players who were formerly contracted by the ACB played an exhibition match in Australia, using the team name "Afghan Women's XI".
